# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The **12-3 incident** (Chinese: 一二·三事件; Portuguese: *Motim 1-2-3*) was a series of political demonstrations and riots against Portuguese colonial rule in Macau which occurred on December 3, 1966.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The incident, inspired by the Cultural Revolution in the People's Republic of China (mainland China), occurred as a direct response to a violent police crackdown by colonial authorities against local Chinese protesters demonstrating against corruption and colonialism in Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Eight protesters were killed by the Macau Police.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Pressured by business leaders in Macau and the Chinese government, the colonial government agreed to meet the demands of the protesters and apologized for the police crackdown.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Portuguese sovereignty over Macau severely diminished after the incident, leading to *de facto* Chinese suzerainty over the territory 33 years prior to the eventual handover of Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The Portuguese foundation of Macau is broadly divided into three different political periods.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The first began with the establishment of the first Portuguese settlement in Macau in 1557 and lasted until 1849.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] During this period, the settlement administrators had jurisdiction only over the Portuguese community.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The second period, known as the "colonial period", scholars generally place from 1849 to 1974.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] It was in this period that the Portuguese colonial administration began to take an active role in the lives of both the Portuguese and Chinese communities in Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] On March 26, 1887, the Lisbon Protocol was signed, in which China recognized the "perpetual occupation and government of Macau" by Portugal, who, in turn, agreed never to surrender Macau to a third party without the consent of the Chinese government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] This was reaffirmed in the Treaty of Peking on December 1, 1887.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Throughout the colonial administration of Macau, the development of Portuguese Macau stagnated due to a complex colonial bureaucracy and corruption.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Racial segregation and division also existed throughout society.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Within the governance of Macau, almost all government officers and civil service positions were held by Portuguese residents.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In September 1945, the Republic of China's (ROC) Ministry of Foreign Affairs expressed to the Portuguese government its desire to hand over Macau back to Chinese control.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] However, due to the Chinese Civil War, discussions between the Kuomintang and the Portuguese were postponed indefinitely.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The founding of the People's Republic of China (PRC) in 1949 caused a large number of refugees and Kuomintang supporters to flee from China to Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Before the 12-3 incident, the Kuomintang and the Chinese Communist Party both maintained a presence in Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] With the founding of the PRC, the Portuguese colonial government opened unofficial relations with the PRC instead of the ROC, primarily due to the proximity of Macau to mainland China via their land border.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Following the founding of the PRC, the influence of the communists grew substantially in Macau, especially among business leaders throughout the colony, while the influence of the nationalists decreased.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Schools and education in Macau were divided along racial lines, with the Portuguese and Macanese sending their children to fully subsidized private schools while the Chinese had to send their children to either Catholic or communist schools.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The segregation of education in Macau was an area of great contention for the local populations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In 1966, residents of Taipa Island, sponsored by the Chinese communists, tried to obtain permission to build a private school.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Despite being granted a plot of land by the Portuguese authorities, Portuguese officials delayed the processing of the building permits, as they had not received any bribes from the residents of Taipa Island.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Despite receiving no building permits from the local administration, local residents began constructing the private school.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] On November 15, 1966, Urban Services Officers on Taipa blocked further construction of the school, leading to a confrontation between Chinese protesters and Macau Police.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The police, including plain-clothes officers, injured over 40 people, of whom 14 were later detained.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In response, a group of around 60 Chinese students and workers demonstrated outside the Governor's Palace in support of the residents of Taipa Island.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The demonstrators shouted revolutionary slogans and read aloud from Mao Zedong's *Little Red Book*.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] On December 3, 1966, demonstrators began to riot and denounced Portuguese authorities for "fascist atrocities".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Protesters, instigated by local communists and pro-Beijing business owners, ransacked Portuguese institutions throughout Macau such as Macau City Hall and the Public Notary's Office.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Violence was also directed towards local Chinese businesses and organizations loyal to the ROC government now located in Taipei.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Unlike in neighboring Hong Kong – which faced similar leftist riots – the business community largely did not back the colonial government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In mainland China, specifically in the province of Guangdong, Red Guards, inspired by the Cultural Revolution and angered by the violence towards Chinese in Macau, began to protest in large numbers at the mainland China–Macau border.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The colonial government subsequently ordered the rioters and demonstrators to be arrested, leading to even more mass discontent and popular support for opposition to the Portuguese administration.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In response, demonstrators toppled the statue of Colonel Vicente Nicolau de Mesquita at Largo do Senado, the city center, and also tore off the right arm of a statue of Jorge Álvares located on the former outer harbor ferry port.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] At the Leal Senado or city hall, portraits of former governors were torn off the walls, and books and city records were tossed into the street and set on fire.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Consequently, martial law was declared, authorizing a Portuguese military garrison and police to crack down on the protests.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Eight protesters were killed by police in the subsequent clashes, while 212 people were injured in total.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Police also arrested 62 people in connection to the protests.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In response to the crackdown, the Portuguese government immediately implemented a news blockade; Portuguese-language newspapers and magazines were banned, and newspapers in Portugal and overseas provinces were ordered to censor reports about the incident.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In response to the incident, the Chinese government deployed the People's Liberation Army to the Chinese-Portuguese Macau border to prevent Red Guards from invading Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Four Chinese warships also entered the waters of Macau in response to the crackdown.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The security ring set around Macau by the Chinese would be involved in multiple casualty-causing conflicts with Red Guards attempting to invade Macau by both land and sea.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The pro-Beijing community in Macau adopted a "Three No's" approach as a means to continue their struggle with the Government: no taxes, no service, and no selling to the Portuguese.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Representing the Chinese community of Macau was the pro-Beijing Committee of Thirteen, chaired by Leong Pui, the leader of the pro-Beijing Macau General Association of Labour.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Negotiations to resolve and prevent further escalation between the PRC, Committee of Thirteen, and the Portuguese government took place in Guangdong.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In contrast, the agreement signed with the Guangdong government was more favorable to the Portuguese; per the agreement, the Chinese government would take back all refugees who arrived in Macau from January 30, 1967, onwards, a promise China would keep until 1978.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] This marked the beginning of equal treatment and recognition of Chinese identity in Macau and the beginning of *de facto* Chinese control over the territory, with Ho becoming the *de facto* governor of Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The Portuguese Foreign Minister Alberto Franco Nogueira described Portugal's role in Macau after 1967 as "a caretaker of a condominium under foreign supervision".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Chinese media described Macau as a "half liberated zone".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Shortly after the agreements were signed, the Chinese military forces around Macau and Red Guards at the border withdrew.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] With the Portuguese now only nominally in control of Macau, political power would increasingly rest with the pro-Beijing trade unions and business leaders.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The official Portuguese and Chinese positions regarding the political status of Macau did not differ, as both now described the region as a Chinese territory under Portuguese administration, and not as a colony or overseas territory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] As a consequence of Beijing's increasing influence, pro-Kuomintang activities in Macau were suppressed; the Republic of China's diplomatic mission was closed, the flying of the flag of the Republic of China was banned, and Kuomintang-run schools were shut down.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] In addition, refugees from mainland China were either barred from entering Macau or forcibly returned to China.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Emboldened by their success against the Portuguese, the Committee of Thirteen encouraged demonstrations against other institutions in Macau that were perceived to be antagonistic towards the PRC.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Specifically, the British Consulate and the Macau Branch of the Hong Kong Immigration department were once again targeted by protesters.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] British consular staff in Macau were under constant threat and harassment by Red Guards, leading to the closure of the British consulate in 1967.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] On April 25, 1974, a group of left-wing officers organized a coup d'état in Portugal, overthrowing the ruling right-wing government that had been in power for 48 years.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The new government began to transition Portugal to a democratic system and was committed to decolonization.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] It carried out decolonization policies and proposed that Macau be given back to China in 1978.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The Chinese government rejected this proposal, believing that an early handover of Macau would impact relations with Hong Kong.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] On December 31, 1975, the Portuguese government withdrew its remaining troops from Macau.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] On February 8, 1979, the Portuguese government decided to break off diplomatic relations with the ROC, and established diplomatic relations with the PRC the next day.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Both Portugal and the PRC recognized Macau as Chinese territory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] The colony remained under Portuguese rule until December 20, 1999, when it was handed over to the PRC.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/12-3-incident] Ho Yin's son, Edmund Ho Hau Wah, would become the first Chief Executive of the Macau Special Administrative Region following the handover of Macau in 1999.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The **14 July Revolution**, also known as the **1958 Iraqi military coup**, was a military coup that took place on 14 July 1958 in Iraq, resulting in the toppling of King Faisal II and the overthrow of the Hashemite-led Kingdom of Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi Republic established in its wake ended the Hashemite Arab Federation between Iraq and Jordan that had been established just six months earlier.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Kingdom of Iraq had been a hotbed of Arab nationalism since the Second World War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Unrest mounted amid economic malaise and widespread disapproval of Western influence, which was exacerbated by the formation of the Baghdad Pact in 1955, as well as Faisal's support of the British-led invasion of Egypt during the Suez Crisis.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Prime Minister Nuri al-Said's policies were unpopular, particularly within the military ranks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Opposition groups began to organize in secret, modelling themselves after the Egyptian Free Officers Movement that overthrew the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Pan-Arabic sentiment in Iraq was further bolstered by the creation of the United Arab Republic in February 1958 under the leadership of Gamal Abdel Nasser, a staunch proponent of anti-imperialist causes.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] In July 1958, units of the Royal Iraqi Army were dispatched to Jordan in support of King Hussein.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] A group of Iraqi Free Officers, led by Brigadier Abdul-Karim Qasim and Colonel Abdul Salam Arif, took advantage of the opportunity and instead marched on Baghdad.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] On 14 July, revolutionary forces seized control of the capital and proclaimed a new republic, headed by a Revolutionary Council.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] King Faisal and Crown Prince Abd al-Ilah were executed at the royal Al-Rehab Palace, bringing an end to the Hashemite dynasty in Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Prime Minister al-Said attempted to flee but was captured and shot a day later.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] After the coup, Qasim assumed the position of Prime Minister and Minister of Defence, while Arif was named Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of the Interior.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] A provisional constitution was adopted in late July.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] By March 1959, the new Iraqi government had withdrawn from the Baghdad Pact and aligned itself with the Soviet Union.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] During the Second World War, Iraq was home to a growing number of Arab nationalists.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] They aimed, in part, to remove British imperial influence in Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] This sentiment grew from a politicised educational system in Iraq and an increasingly assertive and educated middle class.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The two directors of the educational system in Iraq, Sami Shawkat and Fadhil al-Jamal, employed teachers who were political refugees from Palestine and Syria.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] These exiles fled to Iraq because of their roles in anti-British and anti-French protests, and subsequently fostered Arab nationalist consciousness in their Iraqi students.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The growing general awareness of Arab identity led to anti-imperialism.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Similarly, Pan-Arab sentiment grew across the Arab world and was promoted by Egypt's Gamal Abdel Nasser, a rising politician and staunch opponent of imperialism.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Hashemite Iraq faced and confronted these sentiments as well.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Nuri al-Said, the Iraqi Prime Minister during most of the 1930s, 1940s and 1950s, was interested in pursuing the idea of a federation of Arab States of the Fertile Crescent, but was less enthusiastic about a Pan-Arab state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said brought Iraq into the Arab League in 1944, seeing it as a forum for bringing together the Arab states while leaving the door open for a possible future federation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The League's charter enshrined the principle of autonomy for each Arab state and referenced pan-Arabism only rhetorically.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi economy fell into a recession and then a depression following the Second World War; inflation was uncontrolled and the Iraqi standard of living fell.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said and the Arab Nationalist regent, Abd al-Ilah, were continually in opposition to each other, failing to agree on a cohesive economic policy, infrastructure improvements, or other internal reforms.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] In 1950, al-Said persuaded the Iraqi Petroleum Company to increase the royalties paid to the Iraqi government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said looked to the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq's growing oil revenues to fund and propel development.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] He determined that 70 percent of Iraq's revenue from oil was to be set aside for infrastructure development by a Development Board with three foreign advisors out of six total members.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] This foreign presence provoked popular disapproval of al-Said's policy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Despite anti-Western sentiments toward oil and development, al-Said hired Lord Salter, a British economist and former politician, to investigate the prospects for development in Iraq because al-Said's oil revenue reallocation seemed to be ineffective.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Lord Salter continued to make suggestions as to how to implement development projects despite massive Iraqi dislike of his presence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] During the Second World War, the British reoccupied Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] In 1947 prime minister Salih Jabr negotiated British withdrawal, formalised on 15 January 1948 by the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty (also known as the Portsmouth Treaty).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] This agreement included a British and Iraqi joint defence board to oversee Iraqi military planning, and the British continued to control Iraqi foreign affairs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Iraq was still tied to Great Britain for military supplies and training.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] This 25-year treaty was to last until 1973—a duration that Arab nationalists in the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq could not accept.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] As a strong reaction to the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1948, Arab nationalists led the Wathbah Rebellion a year later in protest of the continued British presence in Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said repudiated the Portsmouth Treaty to appease the rebellious Iraqi and Arab nationalists.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] In 1955, Iraq entered into the Baghdad Pact with Iran, Pakistan, and Turkey.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The pact was a defence agreement between the four nations and was endorsed by the UK and the United States as an anti-communist Cold War strategy, but was greatly resented by Iraqis in general.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Egypt saw the Baghdad Pact as a provocation and a challenge to its regional dominance.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] In 1956, when Egypt nationalised the Suez Canal, Iraqi-Egyptian relations were further strained.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] When British, French and Israelis invaded Egypt, Iraq, as a British ally, had to support the invasion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The fact that imperial ties dragged Iraq into supporting this invasion of Arab lands led to wide disapproval across the Iraqi populace, which largely sympathised with Egypt and responded to pan-Arab ideology.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] It felt that the invasion of Egypt was another sign of Western aggression and dominance in the region.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Similarly, when Egypt and Syria united to form the United Arab Republic (UAR) under the banner of pan-Arabism in 1958, Iraqi politicians found themselves in a vulnerable position.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Iraqi leaders had no interest in uniting with Egypt and instead proposed and ratified their own pan-Arab union with Hashemite Jordan in May 1958.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Great Britain and the United States openly supported this union, but many Iraqis were suspicious of its purpose and regarded the Hashemite Arab Federation as another "tool of their Western overlord".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The primary goal of the coup was to liberate Iraq from its imperial ties with the British and the United States.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Western powers dominated all sectors of Iraqi governance: national politics and reform, regional politics with its Arab and non-Arab neighbours, and economic policies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] As a general rule, many Iraqis were resentful of the presence of Western powers in the region, especially the British.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Furthermore, Hashemite monarchic rule could not be divorced from the image of imperial masters behind the monarchy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The monarchy had struggled to maintain power during the Al-Wathbah uprising in 1948 and the Iraqi Intifada of 1952.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] A growing number of educated élites in the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq were becoming enamoured with the ideals espoused by Nasser's pan-Arab movement.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The ideas of **qawmiyah** (Nationalism) found many willing adherents, particularly within the officer classes of the Iraqi military.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said's policies were considered anathema by certain individuals within the Iraqi armed forces, and opposition groups began to form, modelled on the Egyptian Free Officers Movement that had overthrown the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Despite al-Said's efforts to quell growing unrest within the military ranks (such as economic programmes designed to benefit the officer class, and brokering deals with the U.S. to supply the Iraqi military), his position was significantly weakened by the events of the Suez Crisis.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said suffered for his association with Britain; the latter's role in the Crisis seeming a damning indictment of his **wataniyah** policies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Despite al-Said's efforts to distance himself from the crisis, the damage was done to his position.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Iraq became isolated within the Arab world, as highlighted by its exclusion from the "Treaty of Arab Solidarity" in January 1957.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Suez Crisis benefited Nasser's pan-Arab cause while simultaneously undermining those Arab leaders who followed pro-Western policy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said's policies fell firmly within the latter camp, and covert opposition to his government steadily grew in the wake of Suez.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] On 1 February 1958, Egypt and Syria boosted the pan-Arab movement immeasurably with the announcement that they had united as the United Arab Republic (UAR).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The move was a catalyst for a series of events that culminated in revolution in Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The formation of the UAR and Nasser's lofty rhetoric calling for a united Arab world galvanised pan-Arabism in both the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq and the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Their governments attempted something of a response with the creation of the Hashemite Arab Federation on 14 February—a union of the two states—but few were impressed by this knee-jerk reaction to the UAR.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Mutawakkilite Kingdom of Yemen (North Yemen) joined the UAR soon after its formation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Attention then shifted to Lebanon, where Syria sponsored the Arab nationalist movement in its civil war campaign against the pro-Western government of Camille Chamoun.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said recognised that Chamoun's defeat would leave Iraq and Jordan isolated.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] He bolstered Chamoun's government with aid throughout May and June 1958.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] More fatefully, he attempted to bolster Jordan with units from the Royal Iraqi Army, a move that was a direct catalyst for the *coup d'état*.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] On 14 July 1958, a group that identified as the Free Officers, a secret military group led by Brigadier Abdul-Karim Qasim, overthrew the monarchy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] This group was markedly Pan-Arab in character.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] King Faisal II, Prince Abd al-Ilah, and Nuri al-Said were all killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers were inspired by and modelled after the Egyptian Free Officers who overthrew the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] They represented all parties and cut across political factions.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Qasim was a member of the generation that had launched the revolution in Egypt, and had grown up in an era where radicalism and pan-Arabism were circulating in schools, including high schools and military academies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] As a group, most of the Free Officers were Sunni Arabs who came from a modern middle class.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers were inspired by a number of events in the Middle East the decade before 1952.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The 1948 war against Israel was an experience that intensified the Egyptian Free Officers' sense of duty.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] They understood their mission as deposing the corrupt regimes that had weakened a unified Arab nation and thrown their countries into distress.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The success of the Free Officers in overthrowing the Egyptian monarchy and seizing power in 1952 made Nasser a source of inspiration too.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi Free Officer group was an underground organization, and much of the planning and timing rested in the hands of Qasim and his associate, Colonel Abdul Salam Arif.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers sought to ensure Nasser's support and the assistance of the UAR to implement the revolt because they feared the members of the Baghdad Pact would subsequently overthrow the Free Officers as a reaction to the coup.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Nasser only offered moral support, whose material significance remained vague, so Egypt had no practical role in the Iraqi revolution.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The dispatching of Iraqi army units to Jordan played into the hands of two of the key members of the Iraqi Free Officers movement: Arif and the movement's leader, Qasim.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi 19th and 20th Brigades of the 3rd Division (Iraq) (the former under Qasim's command and the latter including Arif's battalion) were dispatched to march to Jordan, along a route that passed Baghdad.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The opportunity for a coup was seized upon by the conspirators.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Arif marched on Baghdad with the 20th Brigade and seized control of the capital, with the help of Colonel Abd al-Latif al-Darraji, while Qasim remained in reserve with the 19th at Jalawla.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] In the early hours of 14 July, Arif seized control of Baghdad's broadcasting station, which was soon to become the coup's headquarters, and broadcast the first announcement of the revolution.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Arif "denounced imperialism and the clique in office; proclaimed a new republic and the end of the old regime...announced a temporary sovereignty council of three members to assume the duties of the presidency; and promised a future election for a new president".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Arif then dispatched two detachments from his regiment, one to al-Rahab Palace to deal with King Faisal II and the Crown Prince 'Abd al-Ilah, the other to Nuri al-Said's residence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Despite the presence of the crack Royal Guard at the Palace, no resistance was offered, by order of the Crown Prince.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] It is uncertain what orders were given to the palace detachment, and what level of force they detailed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] At approximately 8:00 am the King, Crown Prince, Princess Hiyam ('Abd al-Ilah's wife), Princess Nafeesa ('Abd al-Ilah's mother), Princess Abadiya (Faisal's aunt), other members of the Iraqi Royal Family, and several servants were killed or wounded as they were leaving the palace.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Only Princess Hiyam survived, although how and why is unclear.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] With their demise, the Iraqi Hashemite dynasty ended.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Meanwhile, al-Said temporarily slipped the net of his would-be captors by escaping across the Tigris after being alerted by the sound of gunfire.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] By noon, Qasim arrived in Baghdad with his forces and set up headquarters in the Ministry of Defence building.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The conspirators' attention then shifted to finding al-Said, lest he escape and undermine the coup's early success.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] A reward of 10,000 Iraqi dinars was offered for his capture, and a large-scale search began.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] On 15 July he was spotted in a street in the al-Battawin quarter of Baghdad attempting to escape disguised in a woman's abaya.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Al-Said and his accomplice were both shot, and his body was buried in the cemetery at Bab al-Mu'azzam later that evening.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Mob violence continued even in the wake of al-Said's death.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Spurred by Arif to liquidate traitors, uncontrollable mobs took to the streets of Baghdad.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The body of 'Abd al-Ilah was taken from the palace, mutilated and dragged through the streets, and finally hanged outside the Ministry of Defence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Several foreign nationals, including Jordanian and American citizens, staying at the Baghdad Hotel were killed by the mob.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] A mob invaded the British embassy and set it on fire.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The comptroller of the British ambassador's household, Colonel P.L.Graham MC, was shot dead in the embassy building and his body was never recovered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Ambassador and other British embassy staff were lucky to escape with their lives.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] After taking refuge in the registry of the embassy, which the mob threatened to burn down, they were escorted to safety by the Iraqi army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Mass mob violence did not die down until Qasim imposed a curfew, which still did not prevent the disinterment, mutilation and parading of Al-Said's corpse through the streets the day after its burial.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Abdul-Karim Qasim's sudden coup took the U.S. government by surprise.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) Director Allen Dulles told President Dwight D.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Eisenhower that he believed Nasser was behind it.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Dulles also feared that a chain reaction would occur throughout the Middle East and that the governments of Iraq, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Iran would be doomed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The Hashemite monarchy represented a reliable ally of the Western world in thwarting Soviet advances, so the coup compromised Washington's position in the Middle East.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Indeed, the Americans saw it in epidemiological terms.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Qasim reaped the greatest reward, being named Prime Minister and Minister of Defence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Arif became Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of the Interior, and deputy Commander in Chief.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Thirteen days after the revolution, a temporary constitution was announced, pending a permanent organic law to be promulgated after a free referendum.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] According to the document, Iraq was a republic and a part of the Arab nation and the official state religion was listed as Islam.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies were abolished.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Powers of legislation were vested in the Council of Ministers, with the approval of the Sovereignty Council; the executive function was also vested in the Council of Ministers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] On 9 March 1959, *The New York Times* reported that the situation in Iraq was initially "confused and unstable, with rival groups competing for control.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] The new Iraqi Republic was headed by a Revolutionary Council.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] At its head was a three-man sovereignty council, composed of members of Iraq's three main communal/ethnic groups.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Muhammad Mahdi Kubbah represented the Shi'a population; Khalid al-Naqshabandi, the Kurds; and Najib al Rubay’i, the Sunni population.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] This tripartite council assumed the role of the presidency.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] A cabinet was created, composed of a broad spectrum of Iraqi political movements, including two National Democratic Party representatives, one member of al-Istiqlal, one Ba'ath representative and one Marxist.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] By March 1959, Iraq withdrew from the Baghdad Pact and created alliances with left-leaning countries and communist countries, including the Soviet Union.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/14-july-revolution] Because of their agreement with the USSR, Qasim's government allowed the formation of an Iraqi Communist Party.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] A military coup was launched in Bangladesh on 15 August 1975, by mid-ranking army officers in order to assassinate President Sheikh Mujibur Rahman.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, also known as *Bangabandhu* (lit.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] 'Friend of Bengal') or *Mujib*, was the country's founding president, but post-independence his administration grew corrupt and reportedly 'increasingly authoritarian' until he formed a 'one-party state' led by the socialist Bangladesh Krishak Sramik Awami League.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Mujib was killed during the coup, along with many of his family members who were living in Bangladesh at the time, but he was survived by his two then-expat daughters, one of whom was future prime minister Sheikh Hasina.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Abdul Majed, Major Syed Faruque Rahman, Major Khandaker Abdur Rashid and Major Shariful Haque Dalim.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Khondaker Mostaq Ahmad, one of Mujib's close associates and cabinet ministers, took control of the government immediately following the coup with the support of the officers and declared himself President of Bangladesh.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Under martial law, he made a proclamation on 20 August to amend the constitution to omit the provision for the legal basis for the one-party system.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He reportedly praised the assassin officers, calling them "Children of the Sun", and proclaimed the Indemnity Ordinance, which granted them immunity from prosecution.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] They were all later toppled by a counter-coup on 3 November 1975.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] As the democratic demands and protests continued, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman delivered a speech on 7 March that brought the Bengalis together to become prepared for a war of independence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In 1973, Sheikh Mujibur's Bangladesh Awami League won the first parliamentary election in independent Bangladesh by a landslide, but accusations of rigging grew.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In 1973, Shariful Haque Dalim and his wife were involved in a scuffle with the sons of Gazi Golam Mostafa, a leader of the Awami League, at a function at the Dhaka Ladies Club.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In retaliation, some officers and soldiers of the Lancer unit and 2 Field Artillery Regiment of the Bangladesh Army attacked Golam Mostofa's residence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] As a result, Major Dalim, Major S.H.M.B Noor Chowdhury, and other officers were charged with breach of discipline.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Dalim had sought help from President Sheikh Mujib but was refused.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan resigned from the army over the incident.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Dalim and Major Noor were among the officers who lost their commissions over the charges of indiscipline.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In 1974, Sayed Farooq had become dissatisfied with the Awami League government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He would often discuss his dissatisfaction with Major General Ziaur Rahman who was the deputy chief of army staff.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Ziaur Rahman had suggested that Faruque should "do something" about the situation in one such meeting.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Abdur Rashid was able to communicate with Commerce Minister Khandaker Moshtaque Ahmed about the situation in the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Rashid, Dalim, and Moshtaque decided that they must dissolve the one-party system, BAKSAL and remove Sheikh Mujib from power.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Rashid informed Faruque, who agreed with the plan, and he was also told that Major General Zia would support them.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 15 August 1975, President Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was scheduled to attend the convocation ceremony of Dhaka University in the morning.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Before the day on 14 August there was bomb attack in Dhaka University which was suspected to be an attack by the JSD.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] That night, the president's eldest son Sheikh Kamal and the security forces were busy securing the university campus.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On the same day, an Indian military helicopter was reported crashed near Noakhali after hitting a bird, killing the pilot and some of the passengers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Although tension prevailed in various parts of Dhaka city, the situation in Dhaka Cantonment was observed to be normal.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] As the evening of 14 August approached, the vehicles of the army's 2nd Field Regiment were mobilized.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Under the guise of regular night training, 105mm howitzers were towed from a unit south of Dhaka Cantonment to the under-construction Hazrat Shahjalal International Airport in Kurmitola.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Around 10:00 PM, T-54 tanks of the Bengal Lancers emerged from the northern end of the cantonment, eventually concentrating 18 cannons and 28 tanks at the airport.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At 11:30 PM, the participating officers gathered, and in the early hours of 15 August, Major Syed Farooq Rahman, who was in charge of the operation, briefed them on the tactical plan at the squadron office near the airport.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The rebels were divided into four groups, with the primary target being the residence of Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujibur Rahman at Dhanmondi Road 32.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The plan involved two perimeters: an inner circle to launch the direct assault and an outer circle to intercept any reinforcements from the Rakkhi Bahini or the army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Noor and Major Huda were assigned the outer circle, tasked with setting up roadblocks at Dhanmondi Road 27, Sobhanbagh Mosque, and the Road 32 bridge.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Simultaneous attacks were also planned for the homes of Sheikh Fazlul Huq Mani and Abdur Rab Serniabat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Although Major Farooq requested Major Dalim to be present during the attack on the President's house, Dalim took charge of the assault on Serniabat's residence instead, citing "prior relations," and set off with a platoon of soldiers in a truck and a high-speed jeep fitted with a heavy machine gun.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Risaldar Moslemuddin Khan was assigned two platoons to attack Sheikh Mani's house, while Major Shahriar led a company to secure the radio station, Dhaka university, and New Market areas, with the additional task of neutralizing any potential resistance from the BDR at Pilkhana.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Farooq personally led 28 tanks to Sher-e-Bangla Nagar to intercept the Rakkhi Bahini; while these tanks were loaded with machine gun bullets, they carried no shells.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] For the direct assault on the President's house, 350 soldiers in 12 trucks were placed under the command of Major A.K.M.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Rashid had no role in the direct attack but was tasked with coordinating the political situation and post-operation management.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He oversaw 18 cannons, loaded and aimed at the Rakkhi Bahini headquarters and the President's residence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] After the briefing, the groups departed the airport at 4:00 AM.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The residences of Abdur Rab Serniabat and Sheikh Mani were attacked at 5:15 AM, followed by the assault on the President's residence at 5:30 AM.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Former DGFI chief Brigadier Rauf was the first to get such a hint through sources around 2 to 3 AM. but reportedly remained inactive.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Shafiullah claimed, fearing the unknown, Brigadier Rauf immediately left his home and took safe shelter with his family behind the house under a tree who came out in the morning and narrated various unrelated 'stories' to cover up his failure making statements in the newspapers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The head of military intelligence, Lieutenant Colonel Salauddin, received news of the movement of soldiers and tanks between 4:30 AM and 5 AM.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Then he rushed to the house of Army Chief Shafiullah and informed him of the situation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Army Chief Shafiullah kept calling the President, but could not get through.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Army Chief got Brigade Commander Shafaat Jamil on the phone at 5:30 AM.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He ordered Shafaat to move the 1st Bengal and 4th Bengal Regiments to resist the mutineers, but Shafaat Jamil remained inactive claiming that the army chief did not give him any order.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Then the Army chief also spoke to DGFI chief Jamil Uddin Ahmed on the phone.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The DGFI chief rushed to the spot after receiving the President's call and was killed by the mutineers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The army chief got the president on the phone at around 5:50 AM.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The President informed him that his house was under attack.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] After that, there was no response on his phone.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Shafiullah heard gunshots on the phone and the connection was lost soon after.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Then Shafiullah called Deputy Army Chief Ziaur Rahman and Brigadier Khaled Mosharraf and asked them to come to his house.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He also called the Air Chief, the Naval Chief and the station commander of Dhaka Cantonment Colonel Hamid.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] But in the end failed to mount any effective resistance against the rebels.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The President was killed at around 6 am.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The operation at the personal residence of President Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was led by Major A.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Bazlul Huda was placed in the team as he was the adjutant to the 2nd Field Regiment of Artillery, which was guarding the home of the President.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The team also included Major S.H.M.B Noor Chowdhury.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Captain Abul Bashar, who was in charge of the guards, had served under Major Dalim.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Before the attack on his residence at Dhanmondi 32, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman received news of the assault on the home of his relative and cabinet member, Abdur Rab Serniabat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Selim (Abdul) and Abdur Rahman Sheikh (Roma) were sleeping on the balcony outside the room where Mujib was staying.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] From his second-floor room, Mujib telephoned his personal assistant, AFM Mohitul Islam, who was on the ground floor, and instructed, "*Miscreants have attacked Serniabat's residence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Call the police control room immediately.*" After failing to get a response from the police control room, Mohitul attempted to contact the exchange at Ganabhaban (the then President's office).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At approximately 5:30 AM, just as the guards at the residence began hoisting the national flag to the sound of a bugle, a direct attack on the house commenced from the south.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Some of the guards were killed defending the residence after the mutineers tried to force their way in.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The police on duty also started firing back.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Shortly after, Mujib opened the door of his room and stepped out onto the balcony.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Household staff members Abdul and Roma woke up at that time.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Following the instructions of Sheikh Fazilatunnesa Mujib, Roma went downstairs and looked outside the main gate, where he observed members of the army advancing toward the residence while firing.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Returning inside, Roma saw Mujib descending to the ground floor dressed in a lungi and an undershirt.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Upon reaching the second floor, he found Begum Mujib running about in a state of panic.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Roma then went to the third floor and woke up Mujib's eldest son, Sheikh Kamal, and his wife, Sultana Kamal.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] After hearing the news, Sheikh Kamal went down to the ground floor, while Sultana Kamal stayed on the second floor.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Roma also woke up Sheikh Jamal and his wife on the second floor.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Jamal took his wife to Fazilatunnesa Mujib's room on the second floor.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Mujib came down in the middle of the gunfire and started talking to the police on duty.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Everyone assumed that these were sneak attacks by the JSD and the PBSP.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Amidst the gunfire, Mohitul continued to make phone calls to various places from the office in the presence of Mujib.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] During the attempts to reach the police control room and the Ganabhaban exchange, Mujib took the receiver himself and said, "*This is President Sheikh Mujib speaking...*" At that moment, a volley of bullets shattered the window glass and struck the office walls.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] A fragment of the glass injured Mohitul's right elbow.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The firing through that window continued unabated.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Mujib lay down on the floor beside the table and pulled Mohitul down to safety.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Meanwhile, Fazilatunnesa Mujib sent Mujib's kurta and spectacles through the household staff, Abdul.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] When the firing subsided momentarily, Mujib stood up and put on the kurta and glasses brought by Abdul.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Stepping out from that ground-floor room onto the balcony, Mujib questioned the army and police personnel on guard, "*So much firing is going on, what are you doing?*" After saying this, Mujib headed upstairs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] According to the police on duty, Bangabandhu thought that maybe the army men had come to help him this time.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] So, thinking that he would be 'same raid', he ordered the police to stop firing, and then went upstairs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] When the police stopped firing on the order of the President, the attackers easily entered the residence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The guards surrendered after a brief firefight and were lined up outside the house.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Before he could reach the upper floor, Sheikh Kamal came down and stood on the balcony, saying, "*Army and police brothers, come with me.*" Mohitul Islam and Divisional Superintendent of Police (DSP) Nurul Islam Khan stood behind Sheikh Kamal.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At that moment, Major Noor, Mohiuddin Ahmed (Lancer), and Captain Bazlul Huda entered the house gate with their soldiers, shouting "*Hands up.*" Nurul Islam Khan pulled Mohitul inside the room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Without saying a word, Bazlul Huda shot Sheikh Kamal in the leg.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] To save himself, Kamal jumped into the room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He told Mohitul, "*I am Sheikh Mujib's son, Sheikh Kamal.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Tell them.*" Mohitul informed the attackers, "*He is Sheikh Mujib's son, Sheikh Kamal.*" Immediately upon hearing this, Bazlul Huda opened brushfire on Kamal with his sten, resulting in his death.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] During this, one bullet hit Mohitul's knee and another hit Nurul Islam's leg.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In that condition, Nurul Islam dragged Mohitul into his room, where they saw a member of the Special Branch (SB) standing and trembling in fear, with his weapon lying at his feet.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Moments later, Bazlul Huda entered the room and ordered everyone to go outside and line up.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sensing something of what was happening below, Mujib locked the door of his second-floor room and began making phone calls to various places.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At one point, he reached his Military Secretary, Colonel Jamil Uddin Ahmad, and told him, "*Jamil, come quickly.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Tell Shafiullah to send forces.*" Mujib also called the then Army Chief, General Shafiullah, saying, "*Shafiullah, your forces have attacked my house, Kamal seems to have been killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Send forces immediately.*" Shafiullah replied, "*I am doing something.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Can you get out of the house?*" After receiving the call, Colonel Jamil set out for Mujib's residence in his personal red car with his driver, Ayenuddin Molla.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] However, he was shot and killed near the Sobhanbagh mosque; the driver escaped.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On the house compound, Mohitul, Nurul Islam, Abdul Matin, the SB member, and others were lined up.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] One of the attackers shot and killed the SB member.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The attackers then moved upstairs while firing.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] They shot household staff Abdul, who had taken refuge in the washroom of Sheikh Jamal's room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Shot in the hand and stomach, he sat leaning against the wall near the stairs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Besides Mujib, his wife Fazilatunnesa Mujib, sons Sheikh Jamal and Sheikh Russell, and daughters-in-law Sultana Kamal and Parveen Jamal Rosey were inside Mujib's room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The attackers took positions outside the room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] When the firing stopped, Mujib opened the door and stepped onto the balcony, where the attackers surrounded him.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Mohiuddin and his soldiers began leading Mujib downstairs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Where are you taking me?*" Mohiuddin faltered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Mujib asked again, "*Where are you taking me, what will you do—why are you being disrespectful?*" At that point, Bazlul Huda and Nur took positions on the landing between the ground and second floors.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] As Mujib was being brought down, Nur said something, prompting Mohiuddin to step aside.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Immediately, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was fired upon with a sten gun from below.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Eighteen bullets struck his chest and stomach.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Roma followed behind Mujib, the attackers ordered him back into the room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Meanwhile, Mujib's younger brother, Sheikh Abu Naser, who had bullet wounds on his hand, entered the room of Sheikh Rehana (who was abroad).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Roma informed Sheikh Fazilatunnesa Mujib that Mujib had been shot.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At this, Fazilatunnesa Mujib, Sheikh Jamal, Sheikh Russel, Sultana Kamal, Rosey Jamal, Sheikh Naser, and Rama took refuge in the room's washroom.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] After assassinating Mujib, the attackers went downstairs and left the house.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Shortly after, Major Aziz Pasha and Risaldar Mosleuddin entered the house with their troops.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Aziz Pasha went to the second floor and began banging on the door of Mujib's room, eventually firing at it.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Fazilatunnesa Mujib then opened the door and pleaded with them not to kill those inside.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The attackers began leading Fazilatunnesa Mujib, Sheikh Russell, Sheikh Naser, and Rama downstairs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Seeing Mujib's body on the stairs, his wife broke down in tears and cried out, "*I will not go, kill me here.*" When she refused to go down, the assassins took Sheikh Russell, Sheikh Naser, and Roma downstairs, while returning Fazilatunnesa Mujib to the room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Jamal, Sultana Kamal, and Rosey Jamal were already in that room.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Aziz Pasha and Risaldar Mosleuddin then killed everyone in the room, including Fazilatunnesa Mujib, with indiscriminate firing.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Naser, Sheikh Russell, and Roma were then lined up with others on the compound.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Naser told the attackers, "*I don't do politics.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] I earn my living through some business.*" An attacker replied, "*Fine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Go sit in that room.*" He was then taken to the washroom adjacent to the office and shot.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] As the dying Sheikh Naser groaned, "*Water, water*" he was fired upon once more.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Following Aziz Pasha's orders, a Havildar took Sheikh Russell to the second floor and shot him dead.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Faruque promoted Captain Huda to major on the spot.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Fazlul Haque Mani was the nephew of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman and viewed as a likely successor.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He was killed in his home along with his wife, Begum Arzu Moni, who was believed to be pregnant at the time.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] His sons Sheikh Fazle Noor Taposh and Sheikh Fazle Shams Parash survived.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] His home on Road 13/1 in Dhanmondi was surrounded by 20-25 army personnel on 15 August 1975.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Abdur Rab Serniabat, a former minister of water resources and brother-in-law of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, was killed in his home in Mintoo road, Dhaka.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] His home was attacked by a team that was led by Major Aziz Pasha, Captain Majed, Major Shahriar Rashid, and Captain Nurul Huda.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Serniabat's nephew Shahid Serniabat, daughter Baby Serniabat, grandson Sukanto Abdullah Babu, and son Arif Serniabat were also killed in the attack.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Three domestic servants were also killed in the attack.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] His son, Abul Hasnat Abdullah, survived the attack and nine other people were injured in the household.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At Dhanmondi, an artillery group under Colonel Mohiuddin Ahmed took up a position with a M101 howitzer on the lake shore south of Mujib's residence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The mortar shells fired from there towards the residence, missed its target and hit Mohammadpur (to the north of Dhanmondi).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At this, house number 8 and 9 of Shershah Suri Road and house number 196 and 197 of Shahjahan Road (tinshed slum) caught fire instantly killing 14 and leaving 40 people injured.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Under the leadership of Farook, 28 tanks entered the cantonment through the Military Police checkpost at Banani on Airport Road.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] By then, the call to prayer (Fajr Adhan) had begun.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Farook took his tank through the lines of the 46th Brigade unit, following a bypass road to reach the main road of the cantonment.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He entered Tejgaon Airport through a gate opposite the Air Force helipad in Dhaka Cantonment.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] While two tanks followed Farook, the remaining tanks lost their way and proceeded toward Farmgate via Jahangir Gate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Farook then broke through the western wall of the airport and positioned himself in front of the National Rakkhi Bahini headquarters.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Rakkhi Bahini surrendered without incident, Faruque moved towards the residence of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman after the neutralization of the Rakkhi Bahini was completed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The fourth and most powerful group was sent towards Savar to repel the expected counter-attack by the security forces stationed there.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] After a brief fight and the loss of eleven men, the security forces surrendered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The main office of Bangladesh Betar (radio) in Dhaka was attacked by the mutineers early in the morning.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] They quickly disarmed the police stationed there and took control of the radio.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Dalim and Major Shahriar were in charge of the operation at the radio station.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] They controlled the flow of information from there.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Curfew was imposed after Mujib's death was announced on Bangladesh Radio nationwide.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Protests were held in several places including Barguna, Kishoreganj, Bhairab, Khulna, Jessore, Faridganj in Chandpur, Mohanganj in Netrakona, and Gafargaon in Mymensingh.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] During this time, film actor Khasru, also the guerrilla commander of the Dhaka region during the Bangladesh Liberation War, was shot wounded.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Khandaker Mostaq Ahmad addressed the nation from the radio station.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] His speech, written by Taheruddin Thakur, announced the formation of a new government led by him.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Following him, the Chief of the army, his deputy, the chief of naval staff, the chief of the air force, the police chief and Bangladesh Rifles pledged their allegiance to the new government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Khandaker Moshtaque appointed General M.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] General Ziaur Rahman was made the chief of army staff on 24 August 1975 and Khalilur Rahman was made the first Chief of Defence Staff of Bangladesh Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 26 September 1975, Khandaker Moshtaque proclaimed the Indemnity Ordinance which protected those involved in the coup legal protection.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 5 October 1975, the Jatiya Rakkhi Bahini (Absorption in the Army) Ordinance was passed with strong support from Ziaur Rahman; which absorbed the Rakkhi Bahini into the Bangladesh Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 3 November 1975, the situation had grown tense with some officers of the Bangladesh Army led by Brigadier General Khaled Mosharraf and Colonel Shafaat Jamil launching a coup to remove the mutineers and restore order to the Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Justice Abu Sadat Mohammad Sayem replaced Khandaker Moshtaque as president and Mosharraf was made the chief of army staff.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The mutineers in the morning had killed former president Syed Nazrul Islam, former prime minister Tajuddin Ahmed and ministers M Mansur Ali and AHM Qamruzzaman in Dhaka Central Jail where they were locked up since the mutiny on 15 August.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 4 November the mutineers were provided safe passage to Bangkok.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 7 November 1975, Khaled Mosharraf was killed in another coup that restored Ziaur Rahman to the chief of army staff.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The coup was led by the revolutionary soldier's organisation and Colonel Abu Taher.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Taher himself was executed for the killing of Khaled under the government formed by Major General Zia on 21 July 1976, in order to restore discipline in the Army and prevent any further coups.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Abdul Kader Siddique divided 17,000 soldiers into 7 fronts and rebelled against the military junta for 22 months.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Amidst this, the rebellion and struggle of 500 youths from Sherpur Sadar, Sreebardi, Jhenaigati, and Nakla Upazilas, known as the '500 Protesters of Sherpur', was a widely discussed topic.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Arms collection began with surprise attacks on the Police and BDR during the rebellion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At this time, news of arrests started coming from various parts of the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The rebels captured a portion of the border areas of Mymensingh, Sherpur, and Netrokona districts.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The rebels took control of 5 BDR camps and 2 police stations in the border areas.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] A headquarters was established at Chandubhui, a rugged hilly region surrounded by dense forests inside the Meghalaya border.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Kader Siddique served as the Supreme Commander.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Chief Financial Executive was Garo indigenous Chitta Ranjan Sangma.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Chief Recruitment Officer was Abdul Haq, a native of Kamarkhali.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At the same time, a sector headquarters for the rebels was established at Bhabanipur in Durgapur Thana of Netrokona district.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Salim Talukdar of Tangail was responsible as the Sector GOC, and Prashanta Kumar Sarkar was the Second-in-Command.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Quarter Guard Captain was Shariful Islam Khan, and the Defense Commander was Saidur Rahman.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Several sub-sectors were established inside Bangladesh under this headquarters.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 19 January 1976, when rebels attacked Durgapur Thana, the OC of the Thana, Tofail, along with 8 policemen, fled with bullet wounds.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 23 January, after attacking and taking control of Kalmakanda Thana, police officer Ashraf Ali and his wife Sultana Ashraf were detained and taken away.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 20 January, under the leadership of Rangra's Sector Commander Jitendra Bhowmik, rebels attacked Baromari and Farangpara BDR camps and took control of the two camps.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Rebels took possession of a 300-square-mile area in the northern part of the Kangsha River.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] At this time, multiple face-to-face clashes occurred between the rebels and the army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 18 August 1976, 5 freedom fighters of Muktagacha—Jabed Ali, Nikhil Dutta, Subodh Dhar, Dipal Das, and Mofiz Uddin—were killed in an army operation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] A surviving teenage fighter named Bishwajit Nandi was detained and sentenced to death by a military court on 18 May 1977.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Due to the influence of influential world leaders, including Indira Gandhi, he was given life imprisonment and was released in 1989.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The rebellion started in November 1975 and lasted until July 1977.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In this, between 104 and over 400 were killed according to varying opinions, and hundreds were injured.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The rebels surrendered their arms following the military government's general amnesty declaration and promise of rehabilitation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] However, allegations were found that many of the rebels fell victim to enforced disappearances.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The last group of rebels laid down their arms in April 1978.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] In 1976, the military government of Bangladesh provided the coup plotters with diplomatic jobs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Mohiuddin Ahmed was made the second secretary of the embassy in Algeria, Rashed Chowdhury was made the consulate general in Jeddah in Saudi Arabia, S.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Noor Chowdhury was made the second secretary in the embassy in Tehran, Shariful Haque Dalim was made the first secretary to the embassy in Beijing, and Abdul Aziz Pasha was made the first secretary to the embassy in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] They held the positions until 1996, when the Bangladesh Awami League formed the government and recalled them to Bangladesh.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] They refused to comply and as a result were fired from their positions.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Bangladesh Nationalist Party returned to power in 2001 and reinstated the officers who had been dismissed in 1996 to their diplomatic positions.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Colonel Farooq, Colonel Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan, and former state minister Taheruddin Thakur were arrested on 14 August 1996, the same year Bangladesh Awami League returned to power.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Three months later, the indemnity act was removed and the trial began.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] AFM Mohitul Islam, personal assistant to President Sheikh Mujib, filed a charge against the mutineers with Dhanmondi Police Station on 2 October 1996.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The Criminal Investigation Department started investigating the case the next day.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The CID pressed charges against 20 people on 15 January 1997.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 12 March 1997, the trial started with six accused in jail and 14 being outside the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Zobaida Rashid, wife of Khandaker Abdur Rashid, was relieved of charges after she filed a number of appeals, reducing the accused to 19.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Other cases filed with the High Court challenged the legality of the trial court and its location, the cancellation of the indemnity act, which delayed the trial.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Major Huda was bought from Thailand in 1998, through the signing of an extradition treaty between Thailand and Bangladesh.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Dhaka district Justice Kazi Golam Rasul, sentenced 15 accused to death on 8 November 1998.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Appeals were filled with Bangladesh High Court.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 14 November 1998 the High Court delivered a split verdict with Justice Md Ruhul Amin upholding the death penalty of 10 of the convicts, Justice ABM Khairul Haque upholding the death penalty of all 15.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The case was referred to a third Justice, Mohammad Fazlul Karim, who broke the tie by sentencing 12 of the accused to death.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Then Chief Justice Ruhul Amin constituted an appeal court with five justices: Justice Surendra Kumar Sinha, Justice Md Abdul Aziz, Justice Md Tafazzul Islam, Justice BK Das, and Justice Md Muzammel Hossain.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The verdict of the Appellate Division confirmed the death sentences of the 12 convicts on 19 November 2009.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Three sought presidential pardons but were refused.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 27 January 2010, Bangladesh Supreme Court refused the convicts application for review.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On 28 January 2010, five of the convicts in custody were executed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The hanged were Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan, AKM Mohiuddin Ahmed, Mohiuddin Ahmed, Sayed Farooq-ur-Rahman, Bazlul Huda.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On the 7 April 2020, Captain Abdul Majed who was hiding in Kolkata, India, was arrested at Mirpur by the Counter Terrorism and Transnational Crime unit of the Dhaka Metropolitan Police.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He was sent to Dhaka Central Jail, Keraniganj, and was executed by hanging a few days later on the 12 April 2020.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Lawrence Lifschultz characterized this incident as an outcome of the Cold War between the United States-influenced Pakistan and the Soviet Union-influenced India.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] According to Colonel Hamid, The total surprise, suddenness and scale of the attack left all the forces, including the National Defence Force, the police, the BDR, and other forces stunned and terrified thinking it to be a coup by the army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Thus, no one refrained from taking any immediate action without observing the situation well.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] On the other hand, the army chief failed to take a quick decision.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] He wasted valuable time on unnecessary telephone calls and conversations at the critical moment.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] But could not move a single soldier from the cantonment to rescue the president.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Moreover, the insecurity of the President's residence and the failure of intelligence were largely responsible for the death of President Sheikh Mujib.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The radio announcement of Mujib's assassination created terrible psychological pressure in Dhaka and all over the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The announcement was also made in the name of the army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] The participating soldiers followed the orders of their officers, unaware of the coup.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Since 1975, Bangladesh had been under different military governments, with democracy being partially restored a few times and permanently in 1990.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Hasina and Sheikh Rehana, the two daughters of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, survived the assassinations of their family as they were in West Germany in August 1975.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Sheikh Hasina was subsequently elected five times Prime Minister of Bangladesh, in 1996, 2009, 2014, 2018, and January 2024.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/15-august-1975-bangladeshi-coup-d-état] Her regime ended in self-imposed exile following a series of violent protests in 2024.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] Ba'athists involved in the coup as well as the subsequent purge of the moderate faction led by Naif included Hardan al-Tikriti, Salih Mahdi Ammash, and Saddam Hussein, the future President of Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] The Ba'ath Party ruled from the 17 July Revolution until 2003, when it was removed from power by an invasion led by American and British forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] Under the Presidency of Abdul Rahman Arif, who assumed power following the death of his brother Abdul Salam Arif in April 1966, the United States (U.S.) and Iraq developed closer ties than at any point since the 14 July Revolution of 1958.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] (Under Qasim, Law 80 did not impact the IPC's ongoing production at Az Zubair and Kirkuk, but all other territories were returned to Iraqi state control.
