[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] For its part, the ruling Ba'ath Party in Syria did not welcome—or initially even acknowledge—the formation of a government by the rival Ba'ath Party in neighboring Iraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] In a press release, the Syrians mentioned that al-Bakr had been appointed president, but did not mention his party's affiliation, instead referring to the incident as a military coup.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] The Iraqis were more conciliatory, with al-Bakr stating "They are Ba'athists, we are Ba'athists" shortly after the coup.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] When Hafez al-Assad seized power in Syria in 1970, this did not lead to improved relations; to the contrary, the Syrians denounced the Iraqi branch of the party as a "rightist clique".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] The executions led to international criticism, with U.S.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] The victims now were Muslim or Christian Iraqis with the occasional Jew thrown in for good measure." In total, an estimated 150 people were publicly executed in Liberation Square, Baghdad from 1969 to 1970.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] On 1 June 1972, under the direction of Saddam and oil minister Sa'dun Hammadi, Iraq announced Law 69: The nationalization of the Anglo-American shares of the IPC and their transfer to the INOC.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] (The French and Gulbenkian shares of the consortium followed in 1973.) This followed the April 1972 signing of the 15-year Iraqi–Soviet Treaty of Friendship and Co-Operation by al-Bakr and Soviet premier Alexei Kosygin.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] Tripp, the Iraqi–Soviet Treaty upset "the U.S.-sponsored security system established as part of the Cold War in the Middle East," leading the U.S. to finance Mustafa Barzani's Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) rebels during the Second Iraqi–Kurdish War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] From October 1972 until the abrupt end of the Kurdish intervention after March 1975, Gibson states that the CIA "provided the Kurds with nearly $20 million in assistance," including 1,250 tons of non-attributable weaponry.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] However, the U.S. position was an extreme outlier relative to international opinion and none of the U.S.'s traditional allies, including the U.K., were willing to countenance such measures.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] To the contrary, OPEC took decisive steps to ensure the success of Iraq's nationalization.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/17-july-revolution] The IPC consortium broke down and signed an agreement to resolve its outstanding disputes with Iraq on 1 March 1973, leading to celebrations in Baghdad.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] It broke out after the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted a resolution on 29 November 1947 recommending the adoption of the Partition Plan for Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] During the civil war, Palestine's Jewish and Arab communities clashed (the latter supported by the Arab Liberation Army) while the British, who had the obligation to maintain order, organized their withdrawal and intervened only occasionally.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This offensive greatly accelerated the 1948 Palestinian expulsion and flight, which was effected by various violent means, including a number of massacres such as the widely publicized Deir Yassin massacre.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The conflict thus escalated and became the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Under the control of a British administration since 1920, Palestine found itself the object of a battle between Palestinian and Zionist nationalists, groups that opposed both the British mandate and each other.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Britain also reduced Jewish immigration in response to the violence, as legislated by the 1939 White Paper.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After World War II and The Holocaust, the Zionist movement gained attention and sympathy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In Mandatory Palestine, Zionist groups fought against the British administration.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In the two and a half years from 1945 to June 1947, British law enforcement forces lost 103 dead and sustained 391 wounded by Jewish militants.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Palestinian Arab nationalists reorganized, but their organization remained inferior to the Zionists'.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 15 August 1947, the Haganah blew up the house of a Palestinian family near Petah Tikva, killing 12 occupants, including a woman and six children.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After November 1947, the dynamiting of houses formed a key component of most Haganah strikes.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Diplomacy failed to reconcile the different points of view on Palestine's future.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In early November, the Haganah began mobilizing for war, and issued an order that all men between 17 and 25 register.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 18 February 1947, the British announced their withdrawal from the region and on 29 November, the General Assembly of the United Nations voted to recommend the adoption and implementation of the partition plan with the support of the big global powers, though the Arab states opposed it.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A "wind of violence" took hold of the country, foreboding civil war between the two communities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Murders, reprisals, and counter-reprisals resulted in dozens killed on both sides in the process.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The impasse persisted as British forces did not intervene to stop the violence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The first casualties after the adoption of Resolution 181(II) were passengers on a Jewish bus near Kfar Sirkin on 30 November, after an eight-man gang from Jaffa ambushed the bus killing five and wounding others.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Half an hour later they ambushed a second bus, southbound from Hadera, killing two more, and shots were fired at Jewish buses in Jerusalem and Haifa.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This was said to be a retaliation for the Shubaki family assassination, the killing ten days earlier of five Palestinian Arabs by Lehi near Herzliya.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Irgun and Lehi (the latter also known as the Stern Gang) followed their strategy of placing bombs in crowded markets and bus stops.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 30 December, in Haifa, members of the Irgun threw two bombs at a crowd of Arab workers who were queueing in front of a refinery, killing 6 and injuring 42.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] An angry crowd massacred 39 Jewish people in revenge until British soldiers reestablished calm.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In reprisal, soldiers from the Palmach and the Carmeli brigade attacked the villages of Balad ash-Sheikh and Hawassa.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In what became known as the Balad al-Shaykh massacre, between 60 and 70 villagers were killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In early 1948, forces under the command of Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni set up a blockade of Jerusalem, with its 100,000 Jewish residents.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] To counter this, the Yishuv authorities tried to supply the city with convoys of up to 100 armoured vehicles, but the operation became increasingly impractical as casualties in the relief convoys surged.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] By March, Al-Husayni's tactic had paid off.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Almost all the Haganah's armoured vehicles had been destroyed, the blockade was in full operation, and hundreds of Haganah members who had tried to bring supplies into the city were killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation for those who dwelt in the Jewish settlements in the highly isolated Negev and North of Galilee was even more critical.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] From January onward, operations became increasingly militarized.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In all the mixed zones where both communities lived, particularly Jerusalem and Haifa, there were increasingly violent attacks, riots, reprisals and counter-reprisals.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Isolated shootings evolved into all-out battles.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Attacks against traffic, for instance, turned into ambushes as one bloody attack led to another.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 22 February 1948, supporters of Mohammad Amin al-Husayni, with the help of certain British deserters, organized three attacks against the Jewish community.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Using car bombs aimed at the headquarters of the Zionist *Palestine Post* newspaper, the Ben Yehuda St. market, and the backyard of the Jewish Agency's offices, they killed 22, 53, and 13 Jews respectively, a total of 88 fatalities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In retaliation, Lehi put a landmine on the railroad track in Rehovot on which a train from Cairo to Haifa was travelling, killing 28 British soldiers and injuring 35.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This was copied on 31 March, close to Caesarea Maritima, which led to the death of 40 people and injured 60, mostly Arab civilians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] David Ben-Gurion reorganized the Haganah and made conscription obligatory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Every Jew in the country had to receive military training.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This situation caused the United States to withdraw its support for the partition plan and instead propose a trusteeship for Palestine in March 1948, thus encouraging the Arab League to believe that the Palestinian Arabs, reinforced by the Arab Liberation Army, could quash the partition plan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The British, on the other hand, decided on 7 February 1948 to support Transjordan's annexation of the Arab part of Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] While the Jewish population had received strict orders requiring it to hold its ground everywhere at all costs, the Arab population was more affected by the general conditions of insecurity to which the country was exposed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Up to 100,000 Arabs, from the urban upper and middle classes in Haifa, Jaffa and Jerusalem, or Jewish-dominated areas, evacuated abroad or to Arab centres eastwards.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] As a consequence of funds raised by Golda Meir from sympathisers in the United States, and Stalin's decision to support the Zionist cause, the Jewish representatives of Palestine were able to sign very important armament contracts in the East.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Other Haganah agents recovered stockpiles from World War II, which helped improve the army's equipment and logistics.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Jewish Agency had set aside $28 million for foreign arms purchases alone.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] By comparison, the Arab Higher Committee's total budget at this time amounted to $2,250,000, equivalent to the Haganah's annual budget in prewar times.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Several Arab Liberation Army regiments intervened in Palestine, each active in a variety of distinct sectors around the different coastal towns.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They consolidated their presence in Galilee and Samaria.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni came from Egypt with several hundred men of the Army of the Holy War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] German and Bosnian WWII veterans, including a handful of former intelligence, Wehrmacht, and Waffen SS officers, were among the volunteers fighting for the Palestinian cause.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In addition, roughly 100 to 200 British soldiers and police officers, many of whom had developed bitterness towards the Zionist movement and/or pity for the Palestinians over the course of the British counterinsurgency campaign against the Zionists, deserted to help the Palestinians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In contrast, only 17 deserters fought for the Yishuv.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Benny Morris writes that the Yishuv was more successful in attracting and effectively deploying foreign military professionals than its Arab adversaries.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He concludes that the ex-Nazis and Bosnian Muslims recruited by the Palestinians, Egyptians, and Syrians "proved of little significance" to the outcome of the conflict.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In December 1947, the Jewish death toll was estimated at over 200, and, according to Alec Kirkbride, by 18 January 1948, 333 Jews and 345 Arabs had been killed while 643 Jews and 877 Arabs had been injured.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The overall death toll between December 1947 and January 1948 (including British personnel) was estimated at 1,000 people, with 2,000 injured.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ilan Pappé estimates that 400 Jews and 1,500 Arabs were killed by January 1948.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Morris says that by the end of March 1948, the Yishuv had suffered about a thousand dead.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] According to Yoav Gelber, by the end of March, 2,000 were dead and 4,000 wounded.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] These figures correspond to an average of more than 100 deaths and 200 casualties per week among a population of 2,000,000.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Violence kept intensifying with the intervention of military units.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Although responsible for law and order up until the end of the mandate, the British did not try to take control of the situation, being more involved in the liquidation of the administration and the evacuation of their troops.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Furthermore, the authorities felt that they had lost enough men already in the conflict.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The British either could not or did not want to impede the intervention of foreign forces into Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Fawzi al-Qawuqji, Field Commander of the Arab Liberation Army, arrived, according to his own account, on 4 March, with the rest of the logistics and around 100 Bosniak volunteers in Jab'a, a small village on the route between Nablus and Jenin.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He established a headquarters there and a training centre for Palestinian Arab volunteers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In March, an Iraqi regiment of the Arab Liberation Army came to reinforce the Palestinian Arab troops of Salameh in the area around Lydda and Ramleh, while Al-Husayni started a headquarters in Bir Zeit, 10 km to the north of Ramallah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the same time, a number of North African troops, principally Libyans, and hundreds of members of the Muslim Brotherhood entered Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In March, an initial regiment arrived in Gaza and certain militants among them reached Jaffa.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Arab combatants' initial victories reinforced morale among them.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Arab Higher Committee was confident and decided to prevent the set-up of the UN-backed partition plan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation of the 100,000 Jews situated in Jerusalem was precarious, and supplies to the city, already slim in number, were likely to be stopped.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Nonetheless, despite the setbacks suffered, the Jewish forces, in particular Haganah, remained superior in number and quality to those of the Arab forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The high morale of the Arab fighters and politicians was not shared by the Palestinian Arab civilian population.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The UN Palestine Commission reported 'Panic continues to increase, however, throughout the Arab middle classes, and there is a steady exodus of those who can afford to leave the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] 'From December 1947 to January 1948, around 70,000 Arabs fled, and, by the end of March, that number had grown to around 100,000.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] These people were part of the first wave of Palestinian refugees of the conflict.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Mostly the middle and upper classes fled, including the majority of the families of local governors and representatives of the Arab Higher Committee.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Non-Palestinian Arabs also fled in large numbers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Most of them did not abandon the hope of returning to Palestine once the hostilities had ended.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Many decisions were made abroad that had an important influence over the outcome of the conflict.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Britain did not want a Palestinian state led by the Mufti, and opted unofficially instead, on 7 February 1948, to support the annexation of the Arab part of Palestine by Abdullah I of Transjordan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They held that the Arab Legion not enter the vicinity of Jerusalem or the Jewish state itself.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This option did not envisage a Palestinian Arab state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Although the ambitions of King Abdullah are known, it is not apparent to what extent the authorities of Yishuv, the Arab Higher Committee or the Arab League knew of this decision.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The US suggested that Palestine instead be put under UN supervision.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 1 April, the UN Security Council voted on the US proposal to convoke a special assembly to reconsider the Palestinian problem; the Soviet Union abstained.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] This U-turn by the US caused concern and debate among Yishuv authorities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They thought that after the withdrawal of British troops, the Yishuv could not effectively resist the Arab forces without the support of the US.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In this context, Elie Sasson, the director of the Arab section of Jewish Agency, and several other personalities, persuaded David Ben-Gurion and Golda Meyerson to advance a diplomatic initiative to the Arabs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] However, Syria also bought arms from Czechoslovakia for the Arab Liberation Army, but the shipment never arrived due to Haganah intervention.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Possible motivations for Stalin's decision include his support of the UN Partition plan, and allowing Czechoslovakia to earn some foreign income after being forced to refuse Marshall Plan assistance.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The extent of this support and the concrete role that it played is up for debate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Figures advanced by historians tend to vary.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In any case, the embargo that was extended to all Arab states in May 1948 by the UN Security Council caused great problems to them.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Arab leaders did what they could to avoid being directly involved in support for the Palestinian cause.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the Arab League summit of October 1947, in Aley, the Iraqi general, Ismail Safwat, painted a realist picture of the situation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He underlined the better organization and greater financial support of the Jewish people in comparison to the Palestinians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He recommended the immediate deployment of the Arab armies at the Palestinian borders, the dispatching of weapons and ammunition to the Palestinians, and the contribution of a million pounds of financial aid to them.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] His proposals were rejected, other than the suggestion to send financial support, which was not followed up on.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Nonetheless, a techno-military committee was established to coordinate assistance to the Palestinians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Based in Cairo, it was directed by Safwat, who was supported by Lebanese and Syrian officers and representatives of the Higher Arab Committee.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A Transjordian delegate was also appointed, but he did not participate in meetings.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the December 1947 Cairo summit, under pressure by public opinion, the Arab leaders decided to create a military command that united all the heads of all the major Arab states, headed by Safwat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They still ignored his calls for financial and military aid, preferring to defer any decision until the end of the Mandate, but, nevertheless, decide to form the Arab Liberation Army, which would go into action in the following weeks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On the night of 20–21 January 1948, around 700 armed Syrians entered Palestine via Transjordan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In February 1948, Safwat reiterated his demands, but they fell on deaf ears: the Arab governments hoped that the Palestinians, aided by the Arab Liberation Army, could manage on their own until the International community renounced the partition plan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Arab Liberation Army was, in theory, financed and equipped by the Arab League.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A budget of one million pounds sterling had been promised to them, due to the insistence of Ismail Safwat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In reality, though, funding never arrived, and only Syria truly supported the Arab volunteers in concrete terms.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Syria bought from Czechoslovakia a quantity of arms for the Arab Liberation Army but the shipment never arrived due to Hagana force intervention.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] According to Lapierre & Collins, on the ground, logistics were completely neglected, and their leader, Fawzi al-Qawuqji, envisaged that his troops survive only on the expenses accorded to them by the Palestinian population.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] However, Gelber says that the Arab League had arranged the supplies through special contractors.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They were equipped with different types of light weapons, light and medium-sized mortars, a number of 75 mm and 105 mm guns, and armoured vehicles but their stock of shells was small.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation that the Army of the Holy War and the Palestinian forces were in was worse.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They could not rely on any form of foreign support and had to get by on the funds that Mohammad Amin al-Husayni could raise.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The troops' armament was limited to what the fighters already had.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] To make things even worse, they had to be content with arms bought on the black market or pillaged from British warehouses, and, as a result, did not really have enough arms to wage war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Until March, Haganah suffered also a lack of arms.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Jewish fighters benefitted from a number of clandestine factories that manufactured some light weapons, ammunition and explosives.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The one weapon of which there was no shortage was locally produced explosives.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] However, they had far less than what was necessary to carry out a war: in November, only one out of every three Jewish combatants was armed, rising to two out of three within Palmach.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Haganah sent agents to Europe and to the United States, in order to arm and equip this army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] To finance all of this, Golda Meir managed, by the end of December, to collect $25 million through a fundraising campaign set about in the United States to capitalize on American sympathisers to the Zionist cause.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Out of the 129 million US dollars raised between October 1947 and March 1949 for the Zionist cause, more than $78 million, over 60%, were used to buy arms and munition.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] A leased transport plane was used for the Operation Balak first arms ferry flight from Czechoslovakia on the end of March 1948.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] At the beginning of April 1948, a shipment of thousands of rifles and hundreds of machine guns arrived at Tel Aviv harbor.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] With this big shipment, Haganah could supply weapons to a concentrated effort, without taking over the arms of other Jewish territory and risking them being with no weapons.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Haganah went into the offensive, although still lacking heavy weapons.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After 'having gotten the Jews of Palestine and of elsewhere to do everything that they could, personally and financially, to help Yishuv,' Ben-Gurion's second greatest achievement was his having successfully transformed Haganah from being a clandestine paramilitary organization into a true army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ben-Gurion appointed Israel Galili to the position of head of the High Command counsel of Haganah and divided Haganah into 6 infantry brigades, numbered 1 to 6, allotting a precise theatre of operation to each one.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Yigael Yadin assumed the responsibility on the ground as chief of Operations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Palmach, commanded by Yigal Allon, was divided into 3 elite brigades, numbered 10–12, and constituted the mobile force of Haganah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ben-Gurion's attempts to retain personal control over the newly formed IDF lead later in July to The Generals' Revolt.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 19 November 1947, obligatory conscription was instituted for all men and women aged between 17 and 25.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] By end of March 21,000 people had been conscripted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 30 March the call-up was extended to men and single women aged between 26 and 35.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Five days later a General Mobilization order was issued for all men under 40.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] "From November 1947, the Haganah, (...) began to change from a territorial militia into a regular army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] (...) Few of the units had been well trained by December.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] (...) By March–April, it fielded still under-equipped battalion and brigades.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Apart from on the coastline, Jewish yishuvim, or settlements, were very dispersed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Communication between the coastal area (the main area of Jewish settlements) and the peripheral settlements was by road.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] These road were an easy target for attacks, as most of them passed through or near entirely Arab localities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The possibility of evacuating these difficult to defend zones was considered, but the policy of Haganah was set by David Ben-Gurion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He stated that "what the Jewish people have has to be conserved.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] No Jewish person should abandon his or her house, farm, kibbutz or job without authorization.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Every outpost, every colony, whether it is isolated or not, must be occupied as though it were Tel Aviv itself." No Jewish settlement was evacuated until the invasion of May 1948.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Only a dozen kibbutzim in Galilee, and those in Gush Etzion sent women and children into the safer interior zones.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Ben-Gurion gave instructions that the settlements of Negev be reinforced in number of men and goods, in particular the kibbutzim of Kfar Darom and Yad Mordechai (both close to Gaza), Revivim (south of Beersheba), and Kfar Etzion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Conscious of the danger that weighed upon Negev, the supreme command of Haganah assigned a whole Palmach battalion there.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Jerusalem and the great difficulty of accessing the city became even more critical to its Jewish population, who made up one sixth of the total Jewish population in Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The long and difficult route from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, after leaving the Jewish zone at Hulda, went through the foothills of Latrun.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The 28-kilometre route between Bab al-Wad and Jerusalem took no less than three hours, and the route passed near the Arab villages of Saris, Qaluniya, Al-Qastal, and Deir Yassin.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni arrived in Jerusalem with the intent to surround and besiege its Jewish community.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He moved to Surif, a village to the southwest of Jerusalem, with his supporters—around a hundred fighters who were trained in Syria before the war and who served as officers in his army, Jihad al-Muqadas, or Army of the Holy War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He was joined by a hundred or so young villagers and Arab veterans of the British Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] His militia soon had several thousand men, and it moved its training quarters to Bir Zeit, a town near Ramallah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Abd al-Qadir's zone of influence extended down to the area of Lydda, Ramleh, and the Judean Hills where Hasan Salama commanded 1,000 men.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Salama, like Abd al-Qadir, had been affiliated with Mufti Haj Amin al Husseini for years, and had also been a commander in the 1936–1939 Arab revolt in Palestine, participated in the Rashid Ali coup of 1941 and the subsequent Anglo-Iraqi War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Salama had re-entered Palestine in 1944 in Operation Atlas, parachuting into the Jordan Valley as a member of a special German—Arab commando unit of the Waffen SS.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] He coordinated with al-Husayni to execute a plan of disruption and harassment of road traffic in an attempt to isolate and blockade Western (Jewish) Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 10 December, the first organized attack occurred when ten members of a convoy between Bethlehem and Kfar Etzion were killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 14 January, Abd al-Qadir himself commanded and took part in an attack against Kfar Etzion, in which 1,000 Palestinian Arab combatants were involved.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The attack was a failure, and 200 of al-Husayni's men died.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] Nonetheless, the attack did not come without losses of Jewish lives: a detachment of 35 Palmach men who sought to reinforce the establishment were ambushed and killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 25 January, a Jewish convoy was attacked near the Arab village of al-Qastal.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The attack went badly and several villages to the northeast of Jerusalem answered a call for assistance, although others did not, for fear of reprisals.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The campaign for control over the roads became increasingly militaristic in nature, and became a focal point of the Arab war effort.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] After 22 March, supply convoys to Jerusalem stopped, due to a convoy of around thirty vehicles having been destroyed in the gorges of Bab-el-Wad.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 27 March, an important supply convoy from Kfar Etzion was taken in an ambush in south of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] They were forced to surrender all of their arms, ammunition and vehicles to al-Husayni's forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The Jews of Jerusalem requested the assistance of the United Kingdom after 24 hours of combat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] According to a British report, the situation in Jerusalem, where a food rationing system was already in application, risked becoming desperate after 15 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The situation in other areas of the country was as critical as the one of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] The settlements of Negev were utterly isolated, due to the impossibility of using the Southern coastal road, which passed through zones densely populated by Arabs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] On 27 March, a convoy of supplies (the Yehiam convoy) that was intended for the isolated kibbutzim north-west of Galilee was attacked in the vicinity of Nahariya.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p01] In the ensuing battle, 42–47 Haganah combatants and around a hundred fighters of the Arab Liberation Army were killed, and all vehicles involved were destroyed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The second phase of the war, which began in April, marked a huge change in direction, as Haganah moved to the offensive.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In this stage, Arab forces were composed of around 10,000 men among which between 3,000 and 5,000 foreign volunteers serving in the Arab Liberation Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Haganah and Palmach forces were steadily increasing.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In March, they aligned around 15,000 men and in May around 30,000 who were better equipped, trained and organized.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The armed Palestinian groups were roundly defeated, Yishuv took control of some of the principal routes that linked the Jewish settlements, and as a consequence, Jerusalem was able to receive supplies again.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Many mixed cities were taken by the Haganah as well as Jaffa.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Plan Dalet was finalized on 10 March 1948, under the direction of Yigael Yadin.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] 75 pages long, it laid down the rules and the objects that were to be followed by Haganah during the second phase of the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Its principal objective was to secure Yishuv's uninterrupted territorial connections, particularly in response to the war of the roads carried out by Al-Husayni and in preparation for the Arab states' declared intervention.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Plan Dalet caused quite a controversy among historians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Some see it as a plan that was primarily defensive and military in nature and a preparation against invasion, whereas others think that the plan was offensive in nature and aimed at conquering as much of Palestine as possible, or enacted with the aim of ethnically cleansing Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] At the end of March 1948, Husayni's troops prevented supply convoys from reaching Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The city was besieged and the Jewish population was forced to adhere to a rationing system.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion decided to launch the operation Nachshon to open up the city and provide supplies to Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Operation Nachshon marked the Haganah shift to the offensive, even before launching plan D.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The first orders were given on 2 April 1948 with diversion attacks including Qastel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Between 5–20 April 1500 men from the Givati and Harel brigades took control of the road to Jerusalem and allowed 3 or 4 convoys to reach the city.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] All the Arab villages that blocked the route were either taken or destroyed, and the Jewish forces were victorious in all their engagements.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Nonetheless, not all the objectives of the operation were achieved, since only 1800 tonnes of the 3,000 envisaged were transported to the city, and two months of severe rationing had to be assumed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni was killed during the night of 7–8 April, in the midst of the battles taking place in Al-Qastal.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Operation Nachshon exposed the poor military organization of the Palestinian paramilitary groups.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Due to lack of logistics, particularly food and ammunition, they were incapable of maintaining engagements that were more than a few hours away from their permanent bases.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Faced with these events, the Arab Higher Committee asked Alan Cunningham to allow the return of the Mufti, the only person capable of redressing the situation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Despite obtaining permission, the Mufti did not get to Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] His declining prestige cleared the way for the expansion of the influence of the Arab Liberation Army and of Fawzi Al-Qawuqji in the Jerusalem area.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This consisted in poisoning village wells.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the final months of the ensuing 1948 Arab-Israeli war, as Israel gained the upper hand, orders were apparently given to extend the use of biological agents against the Arab states themselves.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Mishmar HaEmek is a kibbutz that was founded by Mapam in 1930, in the Jezreel Valley, close to the road between Haifa and Jenin that passes the Megiddo kibbutz.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It is situated in a place that Haganah officers considered to be on one of the most likely axes of penetration for a 'major Arab attack' against the Yishuv.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 4 April, the Arab Liberation Army launched an attack on the kibbutz with the support of artillery.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The attack was fought off by the members of the kibbutz, who were supported by Haganah soldiers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The artillery fire that had almost totally destroyed the kibbutz was stopped by a British column, who arrived on the scene by order of General MacMillan, and, on 7 April, Fawzi Al-Qawuqji accepted a 24-hour ceasefire, but required that the kibbutz be surrendered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The inhabitants of the kibbutz evacuated their children, and, after having consulted Tel Aviv, refused to surrender.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 8 or 9 April, Haganah prepared a counter-offensive.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Yitzhak Sadeh was put in charge of operations, with the order to 'clean out' the region.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Sadeh's men besieged all the villages around the kibbutz, and the Arab Liberation Army had to retreat to its bases in Jabba.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The majority of the inhabitants of the region fled, but those who did not were either imprisoned or expelled to Jenin.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The villages were plundered by some Kibbutznikim and razed to the ground with explosives with accordance to Plan Dalet.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Morris, the Arab Liberation Army soldiers were demoralized by reports of the Deir Yassin massacre and the death of Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Throughout battle, they had generally been forced to withdraw and to abandon the people of the villages.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Morris, "according to Ben-Gurion, some 640 Haganah soldiers had faced about twenty-five hundred ALA troops, with superior firepower—and bested them".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] When the battle finished, Palmach forces continued 'cleaning' operations until 19 April, destroying several villages and forcing those who inhabited them to flee.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Some villages were also evacuated under the instruction of Arab authorities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In May, Irgun engaged in several operations in the region, razing a number of villages and killing some of their inhabitants, as did some detachments from the Golani and Alexandroni brigades.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Deir Yassin is a village located 5 kilometres west of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 9 April 1948, independently of operation Nachshon, around 120 Irgun and Lehi men attacked the village and ran into resistance, capturing it after a fierce battle with Palmach help.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Irgun and Lehi lost 4 dead and 35 wounded.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Between 100 and 120 inhabitants of the village were killed in the attack, mostly civilians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Haganah had approved the attack and assisted in it.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The operation led to indignation from the international community, the more so since the press of the time reported that the death toll was 254.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion roundly condemned it, as did the principal Jewish authorities: the Haganah, the Great Rabbinate and the Jewish Agency for Israel, who sent a letter of condemnation, apology and condolence to King Abdullah I of Transjordan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 13 April, partly in revenge for the Deir Yassin massacre, a convoy that was driving towards Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital on Mount Scopus was attacked by hundreds of Arabs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the seven-hour battle 79 Jews were killed including doctors and patients.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Thirteen British soldiers were present, but they stood by, only putting in a perfunctory attempt at intervention in the last moments of the massacre.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Lieutenant-Colonel Jack Churchill was present at the scene, and later testified that he had attempted to assist the Hadassah convoy by radioing for support, only for the request to be turned down.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Following the 'fiasco' of Mishmar HaEmek, Fawzi Al-Qawuqji ordered the Druze regiment of the Arab Liberation Army into action, to carry out diversion operations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Druze soldiers took position in several Arab villages 12 kilometres to the east of Haifa, whence they occasionally attacked traffic and Jewish settlements, including Ramat Yohanan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Kibbutznikim and the Haganah soldiers that supported them forced back their attacks and razed the villages from which they launched their attacks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Having run out of ammunition, the Druze withdrew to their base in Shefa-'Amr, with one hundred casualties.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] After an initial failure, a battalion-sized Carmeli force on the night of 15–16 April overran the two villages.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Druze Battalion, on 16 April assaulted the Carmeli positions nine times but the Carmeli troops fought back.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] By afternoon, the exhausted Druze troops retreated.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Druze had already made contact on several occasions with Yishuv agents and following their defeat at Ramat Yohanan, the Druze officers offered to defect and to join the ranks of Haganah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This proposition was discussed with Yigael Yadin, who refused the proposal but suggested that they could help to carry out sabotage operations behind the backs of the Arabs and to influence their comrades into deserting the army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] By the start of May, 212 Wahab soldiers deserted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Taking into account the attitude of his men, Wahab met with Jewish liaison officers on 9 May and agreed to cooperate with Haganah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The two parties avoided clashes, and Wahab created a neutral enclave in the centre of Galilee.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Wahab's army did not respond to calls for it to help fight Haganah's occupation of Acre, and avoided being present while Haganah occupied the police fortress of Shefa-'Amr during its evacuation by the British.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The position that the Druze took influenced their fate after the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Given the good relationship between the Druze and Yishuv from 1930 onwards despite their collaboration with the Arab Higher Council and the Arab League, Ben-Gurion insisted that the Druze, as well as the Circassians and the Maronites benefit from a different position to that of the other Arabs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the context of Plan Dalet, mixed urban centres, or those on the borders of the Jewish state, were attacked and besieged by Jewish forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Tiberias was attacked on 10 April and fell six days later; Haifa fell on 23 April, after only one day of combat (Operation Bi'ur Hametz), and Jaffa was attacked on 27 April but fell only after the British abandoned it (Operation Hametz).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Safed and Beisan (Operation Gideon) fell on 11 May and 13 May respectively, within the framework of Operation Yitfah, and Acre fell on 17 May, within the framework of Operation Ben-Ami.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Arab inhabitants of these towns fled or were expelled en masse.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In these 6 cities, only 13,000 of the total of 177,000 Arab inhabitants remained by the end of May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This phenomenon ricocheted also in the suburbs and the majority of the zone's Arab villages.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Despite the deteriorating situation for the Arabs, a representative of the Arab Higher Committee Representative stated to UN Security Council on April 16 that the Arabs would reject any ceasefire that does not undo the Partition plan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Galilee Panhandle, a zone in northeastern Galilee, between the Lake Tiberias and Metula, was the Jewish-controlled area that was the most distant and isolated from the area most densely populated by Jews, the coastal plain.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The presence of the Lebanese border to the north, the Syrian border to east and the Arab presence in the rest of Galilee made it a probable target for intervention of the Arab armies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Within the framework of the Dalet plan, Yigael Yadin entrusted Yigal Allon, commander of the Palmach, with the responsibility of managing Operation Yiftah, whose objectives were to control all the aforementioned area and consolidate it ahead of the Arab attack that was planned for 15 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Allon was in charge the 1st and 3rd Palmach battalions, which had to face the populace of Safed and several dozen Arab villages.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The situation was made more problematic by the presence of the British, although they began their evacuation of the area.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to his analysis, it was essential that they empty the zone of any Arab presence to completely protect themselves; the exodus would also encumber the roads that the Arab forces would have to penetrate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 20 April, Allon launched a campaign that mixed propaganda, attacks, seizing control of strongholds that the British had abandoned, and destroying conquered Arab villages.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 1 May, a counter-offensive was launched by Arab militiamen against Jewish settlements but was ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 11 May, Safed fell, and the operation finished on 24 May after the villages of the valley of Hula were burnt down.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Syrian forces' planned offensive in the area failed and, by the end of June, Galilee panhandle from Tiberias to Metula, incorporating Safed, was emptied of all its Arab population.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 10 May, Golda Meir and Ezra Danin secretly went to Amman, to the palace of King Abdullah to discuss the situation with him.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The situation that Abdullah found himself in was difficult.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On one hand, his personal ambitions, the promises made by the Yishuv in November 1947 and the British approval of these promises pushed him to consider annexing the Arab part of Palestine without intervening against the future state of Israel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On the other hand, the pressure exerted by his people in reaction to the massacre of Deir Yassin, combined with their feelings with regard to the Palestinian exodus and his agreements with other members of the Arab League pushed him to be more strongly involved in the war against Israel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] He also found himself in a position of power, having the benefit of military support from not only the Arab League, but the British.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Historical analyses of the motivations and conclusions of this meeting differ.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Dominique Lapierre and Larry Collins – as well as Israeli historiographers – the intention behind the Yishuv's negotiation was to obtain a peace treaty and avoid an attack by Arab forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] At that time, the balance of power was not favourable for them, but Meir did not manage to convince the King.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Morris, Abdullah 'reconsidered the promises that he made in November to not be opposed to the partition plan,' but left Meir with the impression that he would make peace with the Jewish state once the civil war had finished.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Avi Shlaim spoke of a 'tacit' agreement to prevent the division of Palestine with the Palestinians, arguing the idea that there was a collusion between the Hashemite Kingdom and Yishuv.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The historian Yoav Gelber, however, rejected this idea and devoted an entire work to dismounting it.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Pierre Razoux indicated that 'the majority of experts consider it probable' that Ben-Gurion and King Abdullah had an understanding over dividing Palestine, and that only the pressure from the Arab states on Abdullah constrained him from following up on his promise.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Razoux, this idea explains the attitude of the British, who, following this plan, would thereby fulfill the promises made by Arthur Balfour to the Yishuv and the Hashemite empire at the same time.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] He states that the presence of Arab Legion troops, before 15 May, near strategic positions held by the British is in this way easy to understand.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ilan Pappé stressed that neither Abdullah's ministers, nor the Arab world itself, seemed to be privy to the discussions held between him and the Yishuv, even if his ambitions on Palestine were widely known.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] He also stated that Sir Alec Kirkbride and Glubb Pasha thought at the time that, at the very least, Azzam Pasha, the Secretary of the Arab League, must have known about Abdullah's double game.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It is certain, on the other hand, that Golda Meir and King Abdullah did not come to an agreement on the status of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 13 May, the Arab Legion took Kfar Etzion, strategically located halfway along the road between Hebron and Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 17 May, Abdullah ordered Glubb Pasha, commander of the Arab Legion, to launch an attack against the Holy City.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Kfar Etzion is a group of four settlements established on the strategic route between Hebron and Jerusalem, right in the middle of Arab inhabited territory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It had 400 inhabitants at the end of 1947.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] After the adoption of Resolution 181(II), it was the object of Arab attacks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion reinforced it on 7 December, protecting it with a Palmach division, but on 8 January, he authorized the evacuation of the women and children of the settlements.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] After 26 March, the last date on which a supply convoy successfully reached it, despite heavy losses of life, the defenders were completely isolated.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 12 May, Arab Legion units started to attack the settlements.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The motivations advanced include their desire to protect one of their last supply convoys before the embargo took effect, which had to travel down the road by Kfar Etzion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Another theory is that the block of settlements obstructed the deployment of the Legion in the area around Hebron, whose attack was one of Abdullah's principal objectives.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] External defences fell quickly, and, on 13 May, the first kibbutz was captured.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Those who were taken prisoner were massacred; only four survived.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Of the 131 defenders, 127, including 21 women, were killed, or massacred after they surrendered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The other three establishments surrendered, and the kibbutzim were first plundered, then razed to the ground.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In March 1949, 320 prisoners from the Etzion settlements were released from the "Jordan POW camp at Mafrak", including 85 women.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The events that took place at Kfar Etzion made apparent the limitations of the policy prohibiting evacuation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Although it was effective during civil war, when facing militias, isolated Jewish settlements could not resist the firepower of a regular army, and an evacuation could have made it possible to avoid the captivity or death of those who defended the settlements.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Ben-Gurion left the final decision to Shaltiel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The battle for Jerusalem was thus set in motion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Operation Yevusi lasted two weeks, from 22 April 1948 to 3 May 1948.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Not all objectives were achieved before the British enforced a cease-fire.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] A Palmach force occupied the strategically located San Simon monastery in Katamon.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Arab irregulars attacked the monastery and a heavy battle evolved.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Both sides had a lot of wounded and killed fighters.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Palmach considered a retreat while the wounded fighters would blow themselves up, but then it was realized that the Arab force was exhausted and could not continue the fighting.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] As a result, the Arab residents left the suburb and the southern besieged Jewish suburbs were released.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Haganah intended to capture the Old City during the final days of the Mandate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Its attacks on the seam between East and West Jerusalem from 13 to 18 May (known as Operation Kilshon) were planned as the initial phase of this conquest.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In Jerusalem, the British held several strategically located security zones named "Bevingrads", at its centre.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The city's radio station, telephone exchange and government hospital were located there, along with a number of barracks and the Notre Dame hostel, which dominated the city.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] One of the main objectives of Operation Kilshon was to take control of these zones of strategic importance while the British withdrew.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 13 May the Haganah extended its control of the Old City's Jewish Quarter and on 14th (having obtained the precise schedule of the evacuation with British complicity) took control of the Bevingrads, including the central post office and the Russian Church compound at 04:00.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] They surprised the Arab troops, who offered no resistance.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] A secondary objective of Operation Kilshon was to simultaneously create a continuous frontline between the various isolated Jewish localities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] For this aim, Brigadier General David Shaltiel, Haganah's former envoy to Europe, was deployed along with a troop of 400 Haganah soldiers and 600 militia soldiers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Emil Ghuri, the new leader of the Army of the Holy War, also envisaged taking these districts and mobilized 600 soldiers for the mission, but prepared no specific operation.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the North of the city, Jewish forces seized Arab-populated Sheikh Jarrah, made a connection with Mount Scopus, and took the villages surrounding the American colony.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the South, they ensured the connection of the German and Greek colonies with Talpiot and Ramat Rahel, after having taken the Allenby barracks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] A Palmach unit even re-established contact with the Jewish district in the Old City via the Zion Gate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The irregular Arabic forces were rendered impotent and yielded to panic, calling the situation hopeless and announcing the imminent fall of the city.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Within the framework of Plan Dalet, Yigael Yadin intended to make a breakthrough in the west of Galilee, wherein a number of isolated Jewish settlements were situated.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This zone, which covers the land from Acre all the way to the Lebanese border, was allocated to the Arabs by the Partition plan, but was on the road through which Lebanese forces intended to enter into Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The command of this operation was entrusted to Moshe Carmel, head of the Carmeli brigade.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It consisted of two phases: the first began on the evening of 13 May, when a column of Haganah's armoured vehicles and lorries advanced along the coast with no resistance.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The forces of the Arab Liberation Army fled without entering battle, and the first phase of the operation finished when Acre was taken on 18 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In the second phase, from 19 to 21 May, troops went as far as the Yehi'am kibbutz by the Lebanese border, connecting it and conquering and destroying a number of Arab villages on the way.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Haganah's move to offensive operations during the second phase of the war was accompanied by a huge exodus that involved 350,000 Arab refugees, adding to the 100,000 displaced during the First wave.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The term 'Palestinian exodus' is often used to refer to both these and two subsequent waves.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] These two waves gained a considerable amount of press interest and were widely relayed in the press of the time, more so than most other Palestine-related events.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The causes of and responsibility for this exodus are highly controversial topics among commentators on the conflict and even historians who specialize in this era.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Among the various possible causes, Efraim Karsh attributes the exodus mainly to Arab authorities' instructions to escape, whereas others argue that a policy of expulsion had been organized by the Yishuv authorities and implemented by Haganah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Others yet reject these two assumptions and see the exodus as the cumulative effect of all the civil war's consequences.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] During the last meeting of the Arab League in February 1948, the Arab leaders expressed their convictions in the capacity of the Arab Liberation Army to help the Palestinians and to force the international community to give up on the UN-backed partition plan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The following summit took place in Cairo on 10 April, with the situation having clearly developed with the death of Al-Husayni and the debacle at Mishmar Ha'emek.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Once again, Ismail Safwat called for the immediate deployment of the Arab state armies at the borders of Palestine, and for the need to go beyond the established policy of participating in little more than small-scale raids towards taking part in large-scale operations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] For the first time, the Arab leaders discussed the possibility of intervening in Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Syria and Lebanon declared themselves ready to intervene immediately, but King Abdullah refused to let the Arab Legion forces intervene immediately in favour of the Palestinians, a move which irritated the Secretary-General of the League, who declared that Abdallah only cedes to the British diktat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Nonetheless, Abdullah declared himself ready to send the Legion to assist the Palestinian cause after 15 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] In response, Syria insisted that the Egyptian army also take part, and, in spite of the opposition of Egypt's prime minister, King Farouk responded favourably to the Syrian request, but due to his aim of curbing the Jordanians' hegemonic goals rather than his desire to help the Palestinians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It was decided that command over the operations would be reserved for King Abdullah, and that the Iraqis would deploy a brigade in Transjordan to prepare for intervention on 15 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 26 April, the 'intention to occupy Palestine' was officially announced at the Transjordanian parliament and the Jewish people were 'invited to place themselves beneath King Abdullah's jurisdiction.' The intention to spare their lives was also promised.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Yishuv perceived this declaration as being one of war and encourages the Western world to pressure the King, through diplomatic means, to prevent his intervention.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 30 April, Jordanians, Egyptians and Iraqis disputed the command of Abdullah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Abdullah received the honorary title of Commander-in-Chief, while the Iraqi general, Aldine Nur Mahmud, was named Chief of Staff.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Despite this show of unity, it was agreed that each army would act independent of each other in the theatre of operations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 4 May, the Iraqi task force arrived at Mafraq.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It was composed of a regiment of armoured tanks, a regiment of mechanized infantry, and twenty-four artillery weapons, and included 1500 men.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Egyptians formed two brigades, deploying around 700 men into the Sinai.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Syrians could not put together a better force, whereas the Lebanese announced that they could not take part in military operations on 10 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] It was only two days before, on 8 May, that the British Foreign Office was certain of the Arab invasion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The state of preparation of the army was such that they did not even have maps of Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] At the time, the final plans of invasion had not even been established yet.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] British leaders tried in vain to make the Arab leaders reconsider their decision, and Ismail Safwat resigned in indifference, but the Arab states seemed resolute.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 15 May 1948, the Arab League announced officially that it would intervene in Palestine to guarantee the security and right to self-determination of the inhabitants of Palestine in an independent state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Benny Morris, the result of these five and a half months of fighting was a "decisive Jewish victory".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On one side, the "Palestinian Arab military power was crushed" and most of the population in the combat zones was fleeing or had been driven out.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] According to Yoav Gelber, during the six weeks between the Haganah offensive on 1 April and the invasion of the Arab armies, the Arabs were defeated in almost every front.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The Jewish forces captured four cities (Tiberias, Jaffa, Safed, and Haifa) and 190 villages; most of their residents fled.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The refugees flooded Samaria, central Galilee, Mount Hebron region, Gaza region, as well as Transjordan, Lebanon, and southern Syria.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] With the defeat of the Palestinian forces and the ALA, the Arab League saw no other option than to invade at the end of the British Mandate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The process of deciding to invade and preparing for the attack began two or three weeks before the end of the Mandate, when the level of the defeat was revealed and it was clear the ALA could not prevent it.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Although the Haganah was somewhat poorly armed, its offensive of the last weeks went well, because Arab villages did not come to the help of their neighboring Arab villages or towns.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Moreover, only a few young Arab men from untouched areas (e.g.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Nablus, Hebron) participated in the fighting in Jerusalem, Haifa, etc.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] Anwar Nusseibeh, a supporter of the Mufti, said the Mufti refused to issue arms to anyone except his political supporters and only recruited his supporters for the forces of the Holy War Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] This partially accounts for the absence of an organized Arab force and for the insufficient amount of arms, which plagued the Arab defenders of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] On 14 May 1948, David Ben-Gurion, on behalf of the Jewish leadership, declared the establishment of the State of Israel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-1948-civil-war-in-mandatory-palestine-p02] The 1948 Palestine war entered its second phase with the intervention of the Arab state armies and the beginning of the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Parliamentary elections were held in Poland on 19 January 1947, the first since World War II.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The largest opposition party, the Polish People's Party, was officially credited with 28 seats; however, the elections were characterized by violence; anti-Communist opposition candidates and activists were persecuted by the Volunteer Reserve Militia (ORMO).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The elections were heavily manipulated, and the opposition claimed that it would have won in a landslide had the election been conducted in a fair manner.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The election gave the Soviets, as well as the Communist-dominated Polish satellite government, enough legitimacy to claim that Poland was "free and democratic", thus allowing Poland to sign the charter of the United Nations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] By 1946, Poland was mostly under the control of the Soviet Union and its proxies, the PPR.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] In 1946, the Communists already tested their strength by falsifying the "3xYES Referendum", and banning the vast majority of right-wing parties (under the pretext of their pro-Nazi stance).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] By 1947, the only remaining legal opposition was the Polish People's Party (PSL) of Stanisław Mikołajczyk.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The Yalta agreement called for "free and unfettered" elections in Poland.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] However, the Kremlin and the PPR had no intention of permitting an honest election.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Soviet leader Joseph Stalin was well aware that if Poland held a free election, it would result in an anti-Soviet government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Conditioned in part by the Hungarian Communists' weak showing in 1945, the PPR proposed to present voters with a single list from all of the legal parties in the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The PSL rejected this proposal almost out of hand.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Eventually, only the PPS, SD and SL joined the Democratic Bloc.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Every electoral district had Democratic Bloc's candidates on List 3.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The January 1947 elections held under the supervision of the PPR fell well short of being "free and unfettered".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The PPR, under the leadership of general secretary Władysław Gomułka, embarked on a ruthless campaign to snuff out the PSL and all other potential opposition.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Over 80,000 members of the Polish People's Party were arrested under various false charges in the month preceding the election, and around 100 of them were murdered by the Polish Secret Police (Urząd Bezpieczeństwa, UB).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] 98 opposition parliamentary candidates were also crossed from the registration lists under these accusations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] In some regions the government disqualified the entire People's Party list under various technical and legal pretenses, most commonly in regions known to be People's Party strongholds.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The electoral fraud was organized and closely monitored by UB specialists, who worked closely with their Soviet counterparts like Aron Palkin and Semyon Davydov, both high-ranking officers from the Soviet MGB.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Bolesław Bierut, head of the provisional Polish parliament (State National Council) and acting president, asked for Soviet assistance in the election.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Over 40% of the members of the electoral commissions who were supposed to monitor the voting were recruited by the UB.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Opposition candidates and activists were persecuted until election day; only the PPR and its allies were allowed to campaign unhindered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The publicized results were falsified, with the official results known to selected government officials long before the actual elections took place and any votes were counted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The real results were not known to anyone.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] In areas where the government had sufficient control, some of the ballot boxes were simply destroyed without being counted, or exchanged with boxes filled with prepared votes.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Where possible, government officials simply filled in the numbers in the relevant documents as per instructions from Soviet and PPR officials without bothering to count the real votes.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] A *Time* article covering the elections noted in its lead paragraph: "In a spirit of partisan exuberance tempered with terror, Poland approached its first nationwide popular election, ten days hence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] By last week most of the combined opposition (Socialist and Polish Peasant Party) candidates had been jailed, and their supporters more or less completely cowed by the secret police, by striking their names from voting lists and by arrest.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The Communist-dominated Government ventured to predict an 'overwhelming' victory." Historian Piotr Wrobel wrote that this election saw "the highest level of repression and terror" that was ever seen during the four decades of Communist rule in Poland.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] In his post-election report to Stalin, Pałkin estimated that the real results (i.e. votes cast) gave the Democratic Bloc about 50% of the vote.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The opposition contended that it had the support of 63 percent of the voting population, and would have received about 80% of the votes, had the elections been free and fair.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The only official electoral document known to exist showed the PSL taking 54 percent of the vote in Kielce Voivodeship to the Democratic Bloc's 44 percent.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Many members of opposition parties, including Mikołajczyk who would have likely become the Prime Minister of Poland had the election been honest, saw no hope in further struggle; fearing for their lives, they left the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Western governments issued only token protests, if any, which led many anti-Communist Poles to speak of postwar "Western betrayal".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] In the same year, the new Communist-dominated legislative Sejm adopted the Small Constitution of 1947, and Bierut, who was also a Soviet citizen, was elected president by the parliament.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Gomułka wanted to adapt the Soviet blueprint to Polish circumstances, and believed it was possible to be both a Communist and a Polish patriot at the same time.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] He was also wary of the Cominform and opposed forced collectivization of agriculture.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] His line was branded as "rightist-nationalist deviation", and he was pushed out as party leader in 1948 in favour of Bierut.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The PSL lingered on for a year and a half under increasing harassment.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] In 1949, the rump of the PSL merged with the pro-Communist People's Party to form the United People's Party.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] Along with the other legal minor party in Poland, the Democratic Party, it was part of the Communist-led coalition; however, this grouping increasingly took on a character similar to other "coalitions" in the Communist world.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] The ZSL and SD were reduced to being mostly subservient satellites of the Communists, and were required to accept the Communists' "leading role" as a condition of their continued existence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1947-polish-parliamentary-election] As a result, this would be the last election in which true opposition parties would be even nominally allowed to take part until the partly free election of 1989.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The **1948 Arab–Israeli War** (15 May 1948 – 10 March 1949), also known as the **First Arab–Israeli War**, followed the civil war in Mandatory Palestine (29 November 1947 – 14 May 1948) as the second and final stage of the 1948 Palestine war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The civil war became a war of separate states with the Israeli Declaration of Independence on 14 May 1948, the end of the British Mandate for Palestine at midnight, and the invasion by a military coalition of Arab states into the territory of Mandatory Palestine the following morning.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The war formally ended with the 1949 Armistice Agreements which established the Green Line.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Since the 1917 Balfour Declaration and the 1920 creation of the British Mandate of Palestine, and in the context of Zionism and the mass migration of European Jews to Palestine, there had been tension and conflict between Arabs, Jews, and the British in Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The conflict escalated into a civil war on 30 November 1947, the day after the United Nations adopted the Partition Plan for Palestine proposing to divide the territory into an Arab state, a Jewish state, and an internationally administered corpus separatum for the cities of Jerusalem and Bethlehem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The civil war began with attacks by Arab militias and mobs on Jewish areas as a reaction to the UN Partition Plan vote.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] As the two communities battled, the British withdrew.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In April 1948, Zionist forces launched an offensive codenamed Plan Dalet, during which they conquered and depopulated cities, villages, and territories in Mandatory Palestine in preparation for the establishment of a Jewish state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Just before the expiration of the British Mandate for Palestine, Zionist leaders announced the Israeli Declaration of Independence on 14 May 1948.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The following morning, Egypt, Transjordan, Syria, and expeditionary forces from Iraq launched an invasion into Palestine, taking control of the Arab areas and attacking Israeli forces and settlements.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The 10 months of fighting took place mostly on the territory of the British Mandate and in the Sinai Peninsula and southern Lebanon, interrupted by several truce periods.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Israel also took control of West Jerusalem, which was meant to be part of an international zone for Jerusalem and its environs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Transjordan took control of East Jerusalem and what became known as the West Bank, annexing it the following year.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The territory known today as the Gaza Strip was occupied by Egypt.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Expulsions of Palestinians, which had begun during the civil war, continued during the Arab-Israeli war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Hundreds of Palestinians were killed in multiple massacres, such as occurred in the expulsions from Lydda and Ramla.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] These events are known today as the Nakba (Arabic for "the catastrophe") and were the beginning of the Palestinian refugee problem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] A similar number of Jews fled or were expelled from the surrounding Arab states in the three years following the war, 260,000 of which went to Israel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Since the 1917 Balfour Declaration and the 1920 creation of the British Mandate of Palestine, and in the context of Zionism and the mass migration of European Jews to Palestine, there had been tension and conflict between Arabs, Jews, and the British.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] British policies dissatisfied both Arabs and Jews.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1920, the Arab leaders were very disappointed with Britain.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1916, the British commander-in-chief in Cairo had made an agreement with the Emir of Mecca: if the Arabs rebelled against the Ottoman Empire, the British would provide them with arms and money and support the formation of an independent Arab state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Around 30,000 older rifles and a smaller amount of modern weapons were supplied by the British, and a very large area from the Red Sea to Damascus was conquered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Britain backtracked from its promise that an independent Arab state would be formed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1920, Britain let French troops attack the Arab Kingdom of Syria, crushing its army and overthrowing its government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Arab opposition developed into the 1936–1939 Arab revolt in Palestine, while the Jewish opposition developed into the 1944–1947 Jewish insurgency in Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 29 November 1947, the United Nations General Assembly adopted a resolution recommending the adoption and implementation of a plan to partition the British Mandate of Palestine into two states, one Arab and one Jewish, and the City of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The General Assembly resolution on Partition was greeted with overwhelming joy in Jewish communities and widespread outrage in the Arab world.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In Palestine, violence erupted almost immediately, feeding into a spiral of reprisals and counter-reprisals.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The British refrained from intervening as tensions boiled over into a low-level conflict that quickly escalated into a full-scale civil war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] From January onwards, operations became increasingly militarised, with the intervention of a number of Arab Liberation Army regiments inside Palestine, each active in a variety of distinct sectors around the different coastal towns.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Having recruited a few thousand volunteers, al-Husayni organised the blockade of the 100,000 Jewish residents of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] To counter this, the Yishuv authorities tried to supply the city with convoys of up to 100 armoured vehicles, but the operation became more and more impractical as the number of casualties in the relief convoys surged.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By March, Al-Hussayni's tactic had paid off.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Almost all of Haganah's armoured vehicles had been destroyed, the blockade was in full operation, and hundreds of Haganah members who had tried to bring supplies into the city were killed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] While the Jewish population had received strict orders requiring them to hold their ground everywhere at all costs, the Arab population was more affected by the general conditions of insecurity to which the country was exposed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] This situation caused the United States to withdraw its support for the Partition Plan, encouraging the Arab League to believe that the Palestinian Arabs, reinforced by the Arab Liberation Army, could put an end to the plan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] However, the British decided on 7 February 1948 to support the annexation of the Arab part of Palestine by Transjordan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Although doubt took hold among Yishuv supporters, their apparent defeats were due more to their wait-and-see policy than to weakness.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] David Ben-Gurion reorganised Haganah and made conscription obligatory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Every Jewish man and woman in the country had to receive military training.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Thanks to funds raised by Golda Meir from sympathisers in the United States, and Stalin's decision to support the Zionist cause, the Jewish representatives of Palestine were able to sign very important armament contracts in the East.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Other Haganah agents recovered stockpiles from the Second World War, which helped improve the army's equipment and logistics.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Operation Balak allowed arms and other equipment to be transported for the first time by the end of March.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Ben-Gurion invested Yigael Yadin with the responsibility to come up with a plan of offence whose timing was related to the foreseeable evacuation of British forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] This strategy, called Plan Dalet, was readied by March and implemented towards the end of April.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] A separate plan, Operation Nachshon, was devised to lift the siege of Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] 1500 men from Haganah's Givati brigade and Palmach's Harel brigade conducted sorties to free up the route to the city between 5 and 20 April.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Both sides acted offensively in defiance of the Partition Plan, which foresaw Jerusalem as a *corpus separatum*, under neither Jewish nor Arab jurisdiction.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Arabs did not accept the Plan, while the Jews were determined to oppose the internationalisation of the city, and secure it as part of the Jewish state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The operation was successful, and enough foodstuffs to last two months were trucked into Jerusalem for distribution to the Jewish population.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The success of the operation was assisted by the death of al-Husayni in combat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] During this time, fighters from Irgun and Lehi massacred a substantial number of Palestinians at Deir Yassin.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The attack was widely publicized and had a deep impact on the morale of the Palestinian population and contributed to generate the exodus of the Arab population.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] At the same time, the Arab Liberation Army was roundly defeated at Mishmar HaEmek in its first large-scale operation, coinciding with the loss of their Druze allies through defection.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] With the implementation of Plan Dalet, the Haganah, Palmach and Irgun forces began conquering mixed zones.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Palestinian Arab society was shaken as Tiberias, Haifa, Safed, Beisan, Jaffa and Acre were all captured and more than 250,000 Palestinian Arabs fled or were expelled.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The British had essentially withdrawn their troops.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] This pushed the leaders of the neighbouring Arab states to intervene, but they were not fully prepared, and could not assemble sufficient forces to turn the tide.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The majority of Palestinian Arab hopes lay with the Arab Legion of Transjordan's monarch, King Abdullah I, but he had no intention of creating a Palestinian Arab-run state, since he hoped to annex as much of the territory of the British Mandate for Palestine as he could.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] He was playing a double game, being just as much in contact with the Jewish authorities as with the Arab League.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In preparation for the offensive, Haganah successfully launched Operations Yiftah and Ben-'Ami to secure the Jewish settlements of Galilee, and Operation Kilshon, which created a united front around Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The inconclusive meeting between Golda Meir and Abdullah I, followed by the Kfar Etzion massacre on 13 May by the Arab Legion led to predictions that the battle for Jerusalem would be merciless.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 14 May 1948, David Ben-Gurion declared the establishment of the State of Israel and the 1948 Palestine war entered its second phase with the intervention of the Arab state armies and the beginning of the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By September 1947, the Haganah had "10,489 rifles, 702 light machine-guns, 2,666 submachine guns, 186 medium machine-guns, 672 two-inch mortars and 92 three-inch (76 mm) mortars".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1946, Ben-Gurion decided that the Yishuv would probably have to defend itself against both the Palestinian Arabs and neighbouring Arab states and accordingly began a "massive, covert arms acquisition campaign in the West", and acquired many more during the first few months of hostilities.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Yishuv managed clandestinely to amass arms and military equipment abroad for transfer to Palestine once the British blockade was lifted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In the United States, Yishuv agents purchased three Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress bombers, one of which bombed Cairo in July 1948, some Curtiss C-46 Commando transport planes, and dozens of half-tracks, which were repainted and defined as "agricultural equipment".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In Western Europe, Haganah agents amassed fifty 65mm French mountain guns, twelve 120mm mortars, ten H-35 light tanks, and a large number of half-tracks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By mid-May or thereabouts the Yishuv had purchased from Czechoslovakia 25 Avia S-199 fighters (an inferior version of the Messerschmitt Bf 109), 200 heavy machine guns, 5,021 light machine guns, 24,500 rifles, and 52 million rounds of ammunition, enough to equip all units, but short of heavy arms.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The airborne arms smuggling missions from Czechoslovakia were codenamed Operation Balak.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The airborne smuggling missions were carried out by mostly American aviators – Jews and non-Jews – led by ex-U.S.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Air Transport Command flight engineer Al Schwimmer.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Schwimmer's operation also included recruiting and training fighter pilots such as Lou Lenart, commander of the first Israeli air assault against the Arabs.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Several Americans, including Schwimmer, were later prosecuted by the U.S. government for violating the Neutrality Act of 1939.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] They were inaccurate but had a loud explosion that demoralised the enemy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Much of the munitions used by the Israelis came from the Ayalon Institute, a clandestine bullet factory beneath kibbutz Ayalon, which produced about 2.5 million bullets for Sten guns.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The munitions produced by the Ayalon Institute were said to have been the only supply that was not in shortage during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Locally produced explosives were also plentiful.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] After Israel's independence, these clandestine arms manufacturing operations were moved above ground.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] All of the Haganah's weapons-manufacturing was centralised and later became Israel Military Industries.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In November 1947, the Haganah was an underground paramilitary force that had existed as a highly organised, national force, since the Arab riots of 1920–21, and throughout the riots of 1929, Great Uprising of 1936–39, and World War II.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] It had a mobile force, the HISH, which had 2,000 full-time fighters (men and women) and 10,000 reservists (all aged between 18 and 25) and an elite unit, the Palmach composed of 2,100 fighters and 1,000 reservists.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The reservists trained three or four days a month and went back to civilian life the rest of the time.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] These mobile forces could rely on a garrison force, the HIM (*Heil Mishmar*, lit.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Guard Corps), composed of people aged over 25.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Yishuv's total strength was around 35,000 with 15,000 to 18,000 fighters and a garrison force of roughly 20,000.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] There were also several thousand men and women who had served in the British Army in World War II who did not serve in any of the underground militias but would provide valuable military experience during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Walid Khalidi says the Yishuv had the additional forces of the Jewish Settlement Police, numbering some 12,000, the Gadna Youth Battalions, and the armed settlers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Few of the units had been trained by December 1947.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 5 December 1947, conscription was instituted for all men and women aged between 17 and 25 and by the end of March, 21,000 had been conscripted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 30 March, the call-up was extended to men and single women aged between 26 and 35.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Five days later, a General Mobilization order was issued for all men under 40.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By March 1948, the Yishuv had a numerical superiority, with 35,780 mobilised and deployed fighters for the Haganah, 3,000 men under Lehi and Irgun, and a few thousand armed settlers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Irgun was eventually absorbed into the Jewish Defence Army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The activities of Irgun was monitored by MI5, which found that Irgun was "involved or implicated in numerous acts of terrorism" during the end years of the British mandate in Palestine such as the attacks on trains and the kidnapping of British servicemen.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Benny Morris, by the end of 1947, the Palestinians already "had a healthy and demoralising respect for the Yishuv's military power" and if it came to battle, the Palestinians expected to lose.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The effective number of Arab combatants was listed as growing to 12,000 by some historians while others calculate an eventual total Arab strength of approximately 23,500 troops, and with this being more of less or roughly equal to that of the Yishuv.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] However, as Israel mobilised most of its most able citizens during the war while the Arab troops were only a small percentage of its far greater population, the strength of the Yishuv grew steadily and dramatically during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Mobilisation for a total war was organised.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Initially, the aim was "simple and modest": to survive the assaults of the Palestinian Arabs and the Arab states.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] "The Zionist leaders deeply, genuinely, feared a Middle Eastern reenactment of the Holocaust, which had just ended; the Arabs' public rhetoric reinforced these fears".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] As the war progressed, the aim of expanding the Jewish state beyond the UN partition borders appeared: first to incorporate clusters of isolated Jewish settlements and later to add more territories to the state and give it defensible borders.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] A third and further aim that emerged among the political and military leaders after four or five months was to "reduce the size of Israel's prospective large and hostile Arab minority, seen as a potential powerful fifth column, by belligerency and expulsion".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to research by Shay Hazkani, Ben-Gurion and segments of the religious Zionist leadership drew parallels between the war and the biblical wars of extermination, and states this was not a fringe position.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] IDF indoctrination pamphlets were distributed to recruits instructing them that God "demands a revenge of extermination without mercy to whoever tries to hurt us for no reason.".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Plan Dalet, or Plan D, (Hebrew: תוכנית ד', *Tokhnit dalet*) was a plan worked out by the Haganah, a Jewish paramilitary group and the forerunner of the Israel Defense Forces, in autumn 1947 to spring 1948, which was sent to Haganah units in early March 1948.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The intent of Plan Dalet is subject to much controversy, with historians on the one extreme asserting that it was entirely defensive, and historians on the other extreme asserting that the plan aimed at maximum conquest and expulsion of the Palestinians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Walid Khalidi and Ilan Pappé, its purpose was to conquer as much of Palestine and to expel as many Palestinians as possible, though according to Benny Morris there was no such intent.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In his book *The Ethnic Cleansing of Palestine*, Pappé asserts that Plan Dalet was a "blueprint for ethnic cleansing" with the aim of reducing both rural and urban areas of Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Yoav Gelber, the plan specified that in case of resistance, the population of conquered villages was to be expelled outside the borders of the Jewish state.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] If no resistance was met, the residents could stay put, under military rule.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Morris, Plan D called for occupying the areas within the UN sponsored Jewish state, several concentrations of Jewish population outside those areas (West Jerusalem and Western Galilee), and areas along the roads where the invading Arab armies were expected to attack.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Yishuv perceived the peril of an Arab invasion as threatening its very existence.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Having no real knowledge of the Arabs' true military capabilities, the Jews took Arab propaganda literally, preparing for the worst and reacting accordingly.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Arab League had unanimously rejected the UN partition plan and were officially opposed to the establishment of a Jewish state alongside an Arab one.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Arab League before partition affirmed the right to the independence of Palestine, while blocking the creation of a Palestinian government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Towards the end of 1947, the League established a military committee commanded by the retired Iraqi general Isma'il Safwat whose mission was to analyse the chance of victory of the Palestinians against the Jews.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] His conclusions were that they had no chance of victory and that an invasion of the Arab regular armies was mandatory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The political committee nevertheless rejected these conclusions and decided to support an armed opposition to the Partition Plan excluding the participation of their regular armed forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In April with the Palestinian defeat, the refugees coming from Palestine and the pressure of their public opinion, the Arab leaders decided to invade Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] We will sweep them into the sea.'" However, Kirkbride notes that Azzam was nervous about the impending conflict; he had not slept the night before.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Gelber, the Arab countries were "drawn into the war by the collapse of the Palestinian Arabs and the Arab Liberation Army [and] the Arab governments' primary goal was preventing the Palestinian Arabs' total ruin and the flooding of their own countries by more refugees.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to their own perception, had the invasion not taken place, there was no Arab force in Palestine capable of checking the Haganah's offensive".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] King Abdullah was the commander of the Arab Legion, the strongest Arab army involved in the war according to Eugene Rogan and Avi Shlaim in 2007.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] (In contrast, Morris wrote in 2008 that the Egyptian army was the most powerful and threatening army.) The Arab Legion had about 10,000 soldiers, trained and commanded by British officers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1946–47, Abdullah said that he had no intention to "resist or impede the partition of Palestine and creation of a Jewish state." Ideally, Abdullah would have liked to annex all of Palestine, but he was prepared to compromise.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] He supported the partition, intending that the West Bank area of the British Mandate allocated for the Arab state be annexed to Jordan.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In order to keep their support to his plan of annexation of the Arab State, Abdullah promised to the British he would not attack the Jewish State.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The neighbouring Arab states pressured Abdullah into joining them in an "all-Arab military invasion" against the newly created State of Israel, that he used to restore his prestige in the Arab world, which had grown suspicious of his relatively good relationship with Western and Jewish leaders.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Jordan's undertakings not to cross partition lines were not taken at face value.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] While repeating assurances that Jordan would only take areas allocated to a future Arab state, on the eve of war Tawfik Abu al-Huda told the British that were other Arab armies to advance against Israel, Jordan would follow suit.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 23 May Abdullah told the French consul in Amman that he "was determined to fight Zionism and prevent the establishment of an Israeli state on the border of his kingdom".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Abdullah's role in this war became substantial.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] He saw himself as the "supreme commander of the Arab forces" and "persuaded the Arab League to appoint him" to this position.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Through his leadership, the Arabs fought the 1948 war to meet Abdullah's political goals.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] King Farouk of Egypt was anxious to prevent Abdullah from being seen as the main champion of the Arab world in Palestine, which he feared might damage his own leadership aspirations of the Arab world.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In addition, Farouk wished to annex all of southern Palestine to Egypt.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Gamal Abdel Nasser the Egyptian Ministry of Defence's first communique describe the Palestine operations as a merely punitive expedition against the Zionist "gangs", using a term frequent in Haganah reports of Palestinian fighters.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Nuri as-Said, the strongman of Iraq, had ambitions for bringing the entire Fertile Crescent under Iraqi leadership.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Both Syria and Lebanon wished to take certain areas of northern Palestine.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] One result of the ambitions of the various Arab leaders was a distrust of all the Palestinian leaders who wished to set up a Palestinian state, and a mutual distrust of each other.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Co-operation was to be very poor during the war between the various Palestinian factions and the Arab armies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Abdullah regarded the attempt to revive al-Husayni's Holy War Army as a challenge to his authority and all armed bodies operating in the areas controlled by the Arab Legion were disbanded.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Glubb Pasha carried out the order ruthlessly and efficiently.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Though the State of Israel faced the armies of multiple neighbouring Arab countries, due to previous battles the Palestinians themselves hardly existed as a military force by the middle of May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] British intelligence and the Arab League reached similar conclusions.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The British Foreign Office and the CIA believed that the Arab states would finally win in case of war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Israeli military historian Martin Van Creveld says the sides were fairly evenly matched in manpower at the beginning of the war, but the ratio shifted in Israel's favor as it went on.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In May, Egyptian generals told their government that the invasion would be "a parade without any risks" and Tel Aviv would be taken "in two weeks." Egypt, Iraq, and Syria all possessed air forces, Egypt and Syria had tanks, and all had some modern artillery.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Initially, the Haganah had no heavy machine guns, artillery, armoured vehicles, anti-tank or anti-aircraft weapons, nor military aircraft or tanks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The four Arab armies that invaded on 15 May were far stronger than the Haganah formations they initially encountered.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The primary Jewish military force in Palestine was the Haganah, which was subordinate to the official leadership of the Yishuv that became the provisional Israeli government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] From November 1947, with the outbreak of the 1947–1948 civil war in Mandatory Palestine, it began reorganizing, changing from a territorial militia to resemble a regular army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By April and May 1948, it was conducting brigade-sized operations.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Mobilization of the Yishuv began during the civil war period with conscription instituted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Following independence it was initially Israel's main military force.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Haganah was joined by two smaller independent militias, the Irgun and Lehi.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] They consisted of political dissidents from the mainstream leadership and at times had come into conflict with the Haganah, but fought alongside it during the civil war and early stages of the war with the Arab states.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 26 May 1948, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion issued an order for the formation of the Israel Defense Forces as the unified military force of Israel, which was ratified by the Israeli cabinet on 31 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The order called for the disbandment of all other Jewish armed forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Subsequently, the Haganah, Irgun, and Lehi were merged into the IDF, although the Irgun and Lehi retained independent presences in Jerusalem and the Irgun recruits into the IDF were initially placed together in their own units.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] After the Altalena Affair, an attempt by the Irgun to import arms in June 1948 that resulted in clashes with the IDF, the independent Irgun units within the IDF were broken up, with the soldiers dispersed between various units.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Following the assassination of Folke Bernadotte by Lehi in September 1948, the Israeli government lost its last remaining tolerance for independent militias and broke up the Irgun and Lehi remnants in Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Training and experience gained by volunteers from the Yishuv in the British Armed Forces during World War II was decisive in building a new military.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Some 30,000 Jews from Palestine served in the British military during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The military training and discipline, organizational skills, and combat experience they gained were of great benefit in building the IDF and fighting the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] They proved important to the Haganah's efforts to train its personnel and helped establish the IDF's General Staff, its artillery, engineering, logistics, and medical services, as well as the fledgling air force and navy.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Veterans of the Jewish Brigade, a British Army brigade group composed primarily of Jews from the Yishuv that fought in the Italian campaign towards the end of the war, were heavily represented in building the IDF, with many Jewish Brigade veterans serving as officers during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] A handful of Yishuv volunteers served as aircrews, including pilots, and hundreds more as ground crews in the Royal Air Force, which would benefit Israel's new air force.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Members of the Yishuv who had served in the Royal Navy and British Merchant Navy during World War II proceeded to serve in the Israeli Navy during the 1948 war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Haganah's elite strike force, the Palmach, had also received British training as preparation for a possible German invasion of Palestine and took part in missions against Vichy French forces in Syria and Lebanon.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In addition, thousands of foreign volunteers, mostly World War II veterans of Allied militaries, served in the IDF during the war in what became known as Mahal, bringing their skills and experience to the IDF.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Most were Jews, but some non-Jews also served.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] They were both ideologically-motivated volunteers and mercenaries.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Most of Israel's air and ground crews were Mahal volunteers from English-speaking countries, resulting in English being the main language of the Israeli Air Force during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Other Mahal volunteers included sailors, tank crews, doctors, and logistics and communications personnel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] As well as experience from World War II, the 1947–1948 civil war against Arab militias prior to the invasion of the Arab armies provided additional combat experience for units and fighters, most of whom were new recruits.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Sources disagree about the quantity of arms at the Yishuv's disposal at the end of the Mandate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Efraim Karsh before the arrival shipments from Czechoslovakia as part of Operation Balak, there was roughly one weapon for every three fighters, and even the Palmach could arm only two out of every three of its active members.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Larry Collins and Dominique Lapierre, by April 1948, the Haganah had accumulated only about 20,000 rifles and Sten guns for the 35,000 soldiers who existed on paper.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Walid Khalidi, "the arms at the disposal of these forces were plentiful".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Benny Morris, on 15 May only about 60% of Haganah troops had weapons, but the amount of weapons available rapidly increased due to massive shipments from abroad as well as domestic manufacturing.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Yishuv forces were organized in nine brigades, and their numbers grew following Israeli independence, eventually expanding to twelve brigades.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Although both sides increased their manpower over the first few months of the war, the Israeli forces grew steadily as a result of the progressive mobilisation of Israeli society and the influx of an average of 10,300 immigrants each month.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By the end of 1948, the Israel Defense Forces had 88,033 soldiers, including 60,000 combat soldiers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] France authorised Air France to transport cargo to Tel Aviv on 13 May.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] After the invasion, France allowed aircraft carrying arms from Czechoslovakia to land on French territory in transit to Israel, and permitted two arms shipments to "Nicaragua", which were actually intended for Israel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Czechoslovakia supplied vast quantities of arms to Israel during the war, including thousands of vz.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] 24 rifles and MG 34 and ZB 37 machine guns, and millions of rounds of ammunition.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Czechoslovakia supplied fighter aircraft, including at first ten Avia S-199 fighter planes.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Haganah agents in Western Europe had amassed fifty 65mm French mountain guns, twelve 120mm mortars, ten H-35 light tanks, and a large number of half-tracks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Haganah readied twelve cargo ships throughout European ports to transfer the equipment, which would set sail as soon as the British blockade lifted at the end of the Mandate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In addition to arms shipments from abroad, Israel's local domestic arms industry produced substantial quantities of weapons and ammunition, as well as dozens of makeshift armored cars and trucks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Following independence, the Israelis managed to build three Sherman tanks from scrap-heap material found in abandoned British ordnance depots.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Israeli agents in Italy subsequently purchased 32 Sherman tanks, which arrived in three shipments from November 1948 to January 1949.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] However, three 75mm M3 tank guns were also purchased in Italy and these were fitted onto three Shermans in time for them to take part in combat.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Haganah also managed to obtain stocks of British weapons due to the logistical complexity of the British withdrawal, and the corruption of a number of officials.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The equipment obtained included twelve armored cars, four of which had cannons, and three half-tracks.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] On 29 June 1948, the day before the last British troops left Haifa, two British soldiers sympathetic to the Israelis stole two Cromwell tanks from an arms depot in the Haifa port area, smashing them through the unguarded gates, and joined the IDF.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] These two tanks would form the basis of the Israeli Armored Corps.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] After the first truce, by July 1948, the Israelis had established an air force, a navy, and a tank battalion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] After the second truce, Czechoslovakia supplied Supermarine Spitfire fighter planes, which were smuggled to Israel via an abandoned Luftwaffe runway in Yugoslavia, with the agreement of the Yugoslav government.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] At the invasion, in addition to the irregular Palestinian militia groups, the five Arab states that joined the war were Egypt, Transjordan, Syria, Lebanon and Iraq sending expeditionary forces of their regular armies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Additional contingents came from Saudi Arabia and Yemen.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] These Arab forces had been trained by British and French instructors; this was particularly true of Jordan's Arab Legion under command of Lt Gen Sir John Bagot Glubb (known as Glubb Pasha).
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Syria bought a quantity of small arms for the Arab Liberation Army from Czechoslovakia, but the shipment never arrived due to Haganah force intervention.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Jordan's Arab Legion was considered the most effective Arab force.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Armed, trained and commanded by British officers, this 8,000–12,000 strong force was organised in four infantry/mechanised regiments supported by some forty artillery pieces and seventy-five armoured cars.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Until January 1948, it was reinforced by the 3,000-strong Transjordan Frontier Force.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] As many as 48 British officers served in the Arab Legion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The commander of the Arab Legion was a British officer, John Bagot Glubb, also known as "Glubb Pasha".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Arab Legion joined the war in May 1948, but fought only in the area that King Abdullah wanted to secure for Jordan: the West Bank, including East Jerusalem.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Jordanian forces were probably the best trained of all combatants.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In the later stages of the war, Latrun proved to be of high strategic importance for its access to roads and proximity to Jerusalem, with some of the most successful Arab and Jordanian fighting occurring there.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1948, Iraq's army had 21,000 men in twelve brigades and the Iraqi Air Force had 100 planes, mostly British.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Initially the Iraqis committed around 3,000 men to the war effort, including four infantry brigades, one armoured battalion and support personnel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] These were to operate under Jordanian guidance.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The first Iraqi forces to be deployed reached Jordan in April 1948 under the command of Gen.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1948, Egypt's army was able to put a maximum of around 40,000 men into the field, 80% of its military-age male population were unfit for military service, and its embryonic logistics system was limited in its ability to support ground forces beyond its borders.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Initially, an expeditionary force of 10,000 men was sent to Palestine under the command of Maj.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] This consisted of five infantry battalions, one armoured battalion equipped with British Light Tank Mk VI and Matilda tanks, one battalion of sixteen 25-pounder guns, a battalion of eight 6-pounder guns and one medium-machine-gun battalion with supporting troops.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Egyptian Air Force had over thirty Spitfires, four Hawker Hurricanes and twenty C47s modified into crude bombers.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Syria had 12,000 soldiers at the beginning of the 1948 War, grouped into three infantry brigades and an armoured force of approximately battalion size.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Syrian Air Force had forty-three planes, thirty-seven operational, of which approximately the ten newest were World War II–generation models.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] France suspended arms sales to Syria, notwithstanding already-signed contracts.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Lebanon's army was the smallest of the Arab states, consisting of 3,500 soldiers, of whom only 1,000 were deployed during the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In 1948, the Lebanese army contained of four infantry battalions, one artillery battalion, one armored battalion, a cavalry group as well as transport engineering and medical support units.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Each infantry battalion averaged 500-550 men, with 450 soldiers per battalion, and contained three infantry companies.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] According to Gelber, in June 1947, Ben-Gurion "arrived at an agreement with the Maronite religious leadership in Lebanon that cost a few thousand pounds and kept Lebanon's army out of the War of Independence and the military Arab coalition".
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] A token force of 436 soldiers crossed into the northern Galilee, seized two villages after a small skirmish, and withdrew.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Israel then invaded and occupied southern Lebanon until the end of the war.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By the time of the second truce, the Egyptians had 20,000 men in the field in thirteen battalions equipped with 135 tanks and 90 artillery pieces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] During the first truce, the Iraqis increased their force to about 10,000.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Ultimately, the Iraqi expeditionary force numbered around 18,000 men.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Saudi Arabia sent hundreds of volunteers to join the Arab forces.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] In February 1948, around 800 tribesmen had gathered near Aqaba to invade the Negev, but crossed to Egypt after Saudi rival King Abdallah denied them permission to pass through Jordanian territory.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] The Saudi troops were attached to the Egyptian command throughout the war, and estimates of their total strength ranged up to 1,200.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] By July 1948, the Saudis constituted three brigades within the Egyptian expeditionary force, and were stationed as guards between Gaza city and Rafah.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] This area came under heavy aerial bombardment during Operation Yoav in October, and faced a land assault beginning in late December which culminated in the Battle of Rafah in early January of the new year.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] With the subsequent armistice of 24 February 1949 and evacuation of almost 4,000 Arab soldiers and civilians from Gaza, the Saudi contingent withdrew through Arish and returned to Saudi Arabia.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] During the first truce, Sudan sent six companies of regular troops to fight alongside the Egyptians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p01] Yemen also committed a small expeditionary force to the war effort, and contingents from Morocco joined the Arab armies as well.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] At the last moment, several Arab leaders, to avert catastrophe – secretly appealed to the British to hold on in Palestine for at least another year.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The civil war in Mandatory Palestine became a war between separate states with the declaration of the establishment of the State of Israel on 14 May 1948, a few hours before the termination of the British Mandate of Palestine at midnight.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The following morning, the regular armies of neighbouring Arab states – Egypt, Transjordan and Syria – invaded the region.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] One ran along the coastal plain from Rosh Hanikra to Rehovot, with two additional appendages emanating from its southern end, one running to West Jerusalem and the other to the Jewish settlement bloc in the Negev which was connected by a sliver of land near Negba.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The other strip was in the Galilee Panhandle, Jordan Valley, and Beit She'an Valley.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] These two strips were narrowly linked by the Israeli-held Jezreel Valley.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Arabs held the rest of Palestine, including a small Arab Liberation Army-supported enclave just south of Haifa.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] Although the Arab invasion was denounced by the United States, the Soviet Union, and UN secretary-general Trygve Lie, it found support from the Republic of China and other UN member states.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The initial Arab plans called for Syrian and Lebanese forces to invade from north while Jordanian and Iraqi forces were to invade from east in order to meet at Nazareth and then to push forward together to Haifa.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] In the south, the Egyptians were to advance and take Tel Aviv.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] At the Arab League meeting in Damascus on 11–13 May, Abdullah rejected the plan, which served Syrian interests, using the fact his allies were afraid to go to war without his army.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] In addition, Lebanon decided not to take part in the war at the last minute, due to the still-influential Christians' opposition, encouraged by Jewish bribes.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] Intelligence provided by the French consulate in Jerusalem on 12 May 1948 on the Arab armies' invading forces and their revised plan to invade the new state contributed to Israel's success in withstanding the Arab invasion.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The first mission of the Jewish forces was to hold on against the Arab armies and stop them, although the Arabs began the war with major advantages such as the initiative and vastly superior firepower.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Egyptian force, the largest among the Arab armies, invaded from the south.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Egyptian invasion was preceded by the entry of smaller forces of Muslim Brotherhood volunteers in April and Egyptian Army volunteers on 6 May, before the end of the Mandate.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] With the end of the Mandate, the Egyptian task force, composed of Egyptian troops and Muslim Brotherhood volunteers, entered the Negev.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The main Egyptian force advanced north in the direction of Tel Aviv while a mixed force of Egyptian troops and Muslim Brotherhood volunteers broke off from the main force and advanced east, occupying Beersheba on 19 May before advancing to the Hebron Hills.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] It participated in combat alongside the Arab Legion and local irregulars at kibbutz Ramat Rachel.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The presence of Israeli kibbutzim along the path of main force's thrust north was seen as a threat due to their potential to cut off forward units and harass supply convoys.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] To secure their flanks, the Egyptians attacked and laid siege to numerous kibbutzim, expending great resources in attempting to capture them.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The defenders of these settlements held out fiercely for days against vastly superior forces, and managed to buy valuable time for the Israelis to reposition their forces and deploy the heavy weaponry now entering the country.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] On 15 May 1948, the Egyptians attacked two settlements: Nirim, using artillery, armored cars carrying cannons, and Bren carriers; and Kfar Darom using artillery, tanks and aircraft.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Egyptians' attacks met fierce resistance from the few and lightly armed defenders of both settlements, and failed.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] On 19 May the Egyptians attacked Yad Mordechai, where an inferior force of 100 Israelis armed with nothing more than rifles, a medium machine gun and a PIAT anti-tank weapon, held up a column of 2,500 Egyptians, well-supported by armor, artillery and aircraft, for five days.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Egyptians took heavy losses, while the losses sustained by the defenders were comparatively light.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] A number of other kibbutzim were heavily shelled but not assaulted.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] During the last week of May, Israeli units of the Negev and Givati Brigades harassed the Egyptians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] In addition, the embryonic Israeli Air Force periodically bombed the Gaza City area, where the Egyptian force's headquarters was located, using converted civilian aircraft.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] On 24 May, the Egyptians reached Majdal and made it their headquarters, briefly stopping and setting up a defensive perimeter.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Egyptians achieved a crucial success when a battalion advanced east from Majdal and managed to link up with the Egyptian force in the Hebron Hills.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Egyptians dug themselves in, cutting off numerous Israeli settlements as well as the Negev Brigade.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] However, this also resulted in Egyptian forces becoming more overstretched.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] On 28 May the Egyptians renewed their northern advance, and stopped at a destroyed bridge north to Isdud.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Givati Brigade reported this advance but no fighters were sent to confront the Egyptians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] Had the Egyptians wished to continue their advance northward towards Tel Aviv, the only Israeli forces positioned to block them were two and a half companies of the Givati Brigade.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] On 2 June, an Egyptian battalion attacked Negba and was beaten back by the kibbutz's 140 defenders.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] The Israelis lost 8 killed and 11 wounded while inflicting an estimated 100 casualties on the Egyptians.
[src:1983-soviet-nuclear-false-alarm-incident/1948-arab-israeli-war-p02] From 29 May to 3 June, Israeli forces stopped the Egyptian drive north in Operation Pleshet.
